window.VIGNETTES = [{"id":"vd_adhd_ir_to_once_daily","stem":"A 9-year-old with ADHD takes immediate-release methylphenidate at breakfast and again at lunch. Symptom control is good while the drug is on board, but the school will no longer administer the midday dose and the family reports marked irritability and loss of control by late afternoon. Which agent best addresses both problems?","options":["Lisdexamfetamine","Dextroamphetamine","Clonidine","Atomoxetine"],"answer":"Lisdexamfetamine","explanation":"Immediate-release methylphenidate has a half-life of only ~2–3 h, which is why a midday dose is needed and why late-day rebound occurs; lisdexamfetamine is given once each morning and its rate-limited conversion to dextroamphetamine gives a smooth ~13–14 h profile that covers the school day without a midday dose. Immediate-release dextroamphetamine still requires morning ± midday dosing, atomoxetine takes 2–4 weeks to work rather than fixing today's coverage gap, and clonidine is sedating and used off-label for ADHD in Canada.","meds":["lisdexamfetamine","methylphenidate","dextroamphetamine","clonidine","atomoxetine"],"disorder":"ADHD","difficulty":1,"tags":["formulation","stimulant","pediatric"],"source":{"name":"Lisdexamfetamine / methylphenidate monographs — pharmacokinetics and dosing","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_adhd_switch_stimulant_class","stem":"A 12-year-old with ADHD has been titrated to an optimal, well-tolerated dose of long-acting methylphenidate over 8 weeks with adherence confirmed, but there has been no meaningful improvement in attention or hyperactivity. There is no misuse risk, no cardiac disease and no tics. What is the most appropriate next pharmacologic step?","options":["Dextroamphetamine","Atomoxetine","Clonidine","Modafinil"],"answer":"Dextroamphetamine","explanation":"Methylphenidate is a pure DAT/NET reuptake blocker whereas amphetamines drive presynaptic release of dopamine and norepinephrine, so failure of one stimulant class does not predict failure of the other — trial the amphetamine class before abandoning stimulants. Atomoxetine and clonidine are non-stimulants reserved mainly for stimulant failure, intolerance or misuse risk (atomoxetine also needs 2–4 weeks to work), and modafinil is a wakefulness-promoting agent that is not a first-line ADHD drug.","meds":["dextroamphetamine","methylphenidate","atomoxetine","clonidine","modafinil"],"disorder":"ADHD","difficulty":2,"tags":["switching","stimulant","mechanism"],"source":{"name":"Methylphenidate vs amphetamine mechanism (deck monograph fields)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_adhd_adjunct_with_tics","stem":"A 13-year-old is on an optimally dosed long-acting stimulant with a partial response: he still has disruptive impulsivity late in the day, and he has mild pre-existing motor tics that the family does not want to worsen. You want to add a second agent that carries a Canadian indication as an adjunct to a stimulant. Which do you add?","options":["Guanfacine XR","Clonidine","Atomoxetine","Modafinil"],"answer":"Guanfacine XR","explanation":"Guanfacine XR is the α2A-selective agonist approved in Canada for ADHD both as monotherapy and as an adjunct to a stimulant, and it is also used off-label for tics — so it fits a partial stimulant responder with tics. Clonidine's ADHD use in Canada is off-label and it is markedly more sedating, atomoxetine has no adjunct-to-stimulant indication, and modafinil is a wakefulness agent with no ADHD indication. Monitor BP/HR and sedation, and taper guanfacine rather than stopping abruptly (rebound hypertension).","meds":["guanfacine","clonidine","atomoxetine","modafinil"],"disorder":"ADHD","difficulty":2,"tags":["adjunct","tics","non-stimulant"],"source":{"name":"Guanfacine XR monograph — ADHD monotherapy or stimulant adjunct","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_adhd_hepatotoxicity_atomoxetine","stem":"A 28-year-old treated for ADHD for four months presents with jaundice, dark urine, pruritus and right-upper-quadrant discomfort. ALT and AST are markedly elevated with a rising bilirubin; viral serologies and an ultrasound are unremarkable, and she drinks no alcohol. Which of her possible ADHD medications is the most likely cause?","options":["Atomoxetine","Methylphenidate","Guanfacine XR","Clonidine"],"answer":"Atomoxetine","explanation":"Atomoxetine carries a rare but potentially severe drug-induced liver injury signal — jaundice or markedly elevated liver enzymes mandate permanent discontinuation with no rechallenge. Methylphenidate is de-esterified by carboxylesterase to inactive ritalinic acid, and guanfacine and clonidine are characterised by sedation, bradycardia and hypotension rather than hepatotoxicity.","meds":["atomoxetine","methylphenidate","guanfacine","clonidine"],"disorder":"ADHD","difficulty":2,"tags":["hepatic","adverse-effect","monitoring"],"source":{"name":"Atomoxetine monograph — hepatotoxicity warning","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_adhd_cyp2d6_paroxetine","stem":"A 35-year-old man with major depressive disorder is doing well on paroxetine, which he does not want to change, and now needs pharmacotherapy for adult ADHD. Which agent's exposure is LEAST likely to be altered by paroxetine's potent CYP2D6 inhibition?","options":["Methylphenidate","Atomoxetine","Dextroamphetamine","Mixed Amphetamine Salts"],"answer":"Methylphenidate","explanation":"Methylphenidate is de-esterified by carboxylesterase CES1A1 with minimal CYP involvement, so it has comparatively few pharmacokinetic interactions. Atomoxetine is a CYP2D6 substrate whose levels rise markedly with paroxetine, fluoxetine or quinidine (start low and titrate slowly), and both dextroamphetamine and mixed amphetamine salts undergo CYP2D6-dependent metabolism, so 2D6 inhibitors can raise amphetamine exposure.","meds":["methylphenidate","atomoxetine","dextroamphetamine","amphetamine_salts","paroxetine"],"disorder":"ADHD","difficulty":3,"tags":["interaction","cyp2d6","pharmacokinetics"],"source":{"name":"Methylphenidate (CES1) and atomoxetine (CYP2D6) monographs","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_adhd_pregnancy_avoid_modafinil","stem":"A 27-year-old woman with ADHD is actively planning a pregnancy and asks you to review her options. Which agent carries an explicit recommendation to AVOID use in pregnancy, plus a specific need for backup contraception if it is continued?","options":["Modafinil","Methylphenidate","Atomoxetine","Guanfacine XR"],"answer":"Modafinil","explanation":"Modafinil is to be avoided in pregnancy given signals of intrauterine growth restriction and congenital anomalies, and it induces CYP3A4 — reducing hormonal contraceptive efficacy during use and for about a month afterwards, so backup contraception must be counselled. Methylphenidate, atomoxetine and guanfacine XR all have limited human pregnancy data requiring an individualized risk–benefit decision, but none carries modafinil's explicit avoid-plus-contraception warning.","meds":["modafinil","methylphenidate","atomoxetine","guanfacine"],"disorder":"ADHD","difficulty":3,"tags":["pregnancy","interaction","special-population"],"source":{"name":"Modafinil monograph — pregnancy and CYP3A4 induction","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_adhd_bipolar_mania_risk","stem":"A 25-year-old with bipolar I disorder, euthymic on lithium for the past year, is referred for treatment of longstanding ADHD symptoms. Which of the following agents carries the greatest risk of precipitating a manic or psychotic episode and therefore demands the most careful screening and mood surveillance before it is started?","options":["Mixed Amphetamine Salts","Guanfacine XR","Clonidine","Atomoxetine"],"answer":"Mixed Amphetamine Salts","explanation":"Stimulant labels list new or worsened mania and psychosis among their serious adverse effects and specifically direct prescribers to screen for risk factors for a manic episode before starting and to reconsider the drug if manic or psychotic symptoms emerge. The α2 agonists guanfacine XR and clonidine and the non-stimulant atomoxetine do not carry that mania signal — their characteristic risks are sedation, bradycardia and hypotension (α2 agonists) and hepatotoxicity and youth suicidality (atomoxetine).","meds":["amphetamine_salts","guanfacine","clonidine","atomoxetine","lithium"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["mania","special-population","screening"],"source":{"name":"Amphetamine monograph — psychiatric adverse reactions / pretreatment screening","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_adhd_growth_suppression_switch","stem":"An 8-year-old has been on a stimulant for 18 months. ADHD control is adequate, but his appetite is poor, his weight has fallen from the 50th to the 15th percentile and he has crossed down two height percentiles despite calorie-dense meals and evening snacks. The family wants an agent that does not carry the stimulant class's growth warning. Which do you switch to?","options":["Guanfacine XR","Lisdexamfetamine","Methylphenidate","Dextroamphetamine"],"answer":"Guanfacine XR","explanation":"Long-term growth suppression is a labelled serious adverse effect shared by all the stimulants, so switching among methylphenidate, lisdexamfetamine and dextroamphetamine will not solve it; guanfacine XR is a non-stimulant α2A agonist whose monitoring burden is blood pressure, heart rate and sedation rather than growth suppression. Height and weight should still be plotted at each visit on any ADHD medication.","meds":["guanfacine","lisdexamfetamine","methylphenidate","dextroamphetamine"],"disorder":"ADHD","difficulty":2,"tags":["growth","monitoring","pediatric"],"source":{"name":"Stimulant monographs — long-term suppression of growth in pediatric patients","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_adhd_toddler_ingestion_clonidine","stem":"A 2-year-old is found beside an open pill bottle belonging to his older brother, who is treated for ADHD. In the emergency department the toddler is deeply lethargic with a respiratory rate of 10, heart rate 52, blood pressure 72/40 and pinpoint pupils. Naloxone produces no convincing response. Which medication did he most likely ingest?","options":["Clonidine","Methylphenidate","Lisdexamfetamine","Atomoxetine"],"answer":"Clonidine","explanation":"Clonidine overdose in a small child produces CNS and respiratory depression, bradycardia, hypotension and miosis — a picture that mimics opioid toxicity but responds only variably to naloxone, and even small ingestions can be lethal, so management is supportive with cardiac monitoring. Methylphenidate and lisdexamfetamine would instead cause a sympathomimetic picture (agitation, tachycardia, hypertension, mydriasis, hyperthermia), and atomoxetine overdose typically causes somnolence, agitation and tachycardia rather than profound bradycardia with miosis.","meds":["clonidine","methylphenidate","lisdexamfetamine","atomoxetine"],"disorder":"ADHD","difficulty":3,"tags":["overdose","pediatric","safety"],"source":{"name":"Clonidine monograph — overdose in young children","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_adhd_sympathomimetic_toxidrome","stem":"A 19-year-old university student is brought in after swallowing a handful of a friend's mixed amphetamine salts capsules. He is agitated and diaphoretic with heart rate 148, blood pressure 195/115, temperature 39.4°C and dilated pupils. Tone is normal with no rigidity and no inducible clonus, and he is on no other medication. Which syndrome does this represent?","options":["Sympathomimetic toxicity","Anticholinergic toxicity","Serotonin syndrome","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome"],"answer":"Sympathomimetic toxicity","explanation":"Amphetamine overdose produces a sympathomimetic crisis — agitation, hypertension, tachyarrhythmia, hyperthermia, mydriasis and seizures — and diaphoresis with preserved normal tone is the key discriminator; benzodiazepines plus cooling and supportive care are first-line. Anticholinergic toxicity gives dry flushed skin and urinary retention, serotonin syndrome requires a serotonergic agent and features clonus and hyperreflexia, and neuroleptic malignant syndrome follows dopamine blockade with lead-pipe rigidity evolving over days.","meds":["amphetamine_salts","dextroamphetamine","lisdexamfetamine"],"disorder":"ADHD","difficulty":2,"tags":["overdose","toxidrome","safety"],"source":{"name":"Amphetamine monograph — overdosage","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_adhd_stimulant_insomnia_melatonin","stem":"A 9-year-old on lisdexamfetamine has excellent daytime ADHD control that the family does not want to give up, but sleep-onset latency is consistently over 90 minutes despite good sleep hygiene and a morning-only dosing schedule. The parents ask for the option with the widest safety margin and no dependence risk. What do you recommend?","options":["Melatonin","Clonidine","Zopiclone","Temazepam"],"answer":"Melatonin","explanation":"Melatonin is an MT1/MT2 agonist used for sleep onset in ADHD, has a very wide safety margin with no dependence, and in Canada is sold over the counter as a Natural Health Product (NPN, not a DIN). Bedtime clonidine is an alternative but adds sedation, bradycardia, hypotension and rebound hypertension on abrupt withdrawal, while the Z-drug zopiclone and the benzodiazepine temazepam carry dependence, next-day impairment and no pediatric role.","meds":["melatonin","clonidine","zopiclone","temazepam","lisdexamfetamine"],"disorder":"Insomnia","difficulty":2,"tags":["insomnia","pediatric","adjunct"],"source":{"name":"Melatonin and clonidine deck entries — sleep onset in ADHD","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vd_adhd_comorbid_smoking_varenicline","stem":"A 34-year-old with ADHD, stable and well controlled on lisdexamfetamine, smokes a pack a day and has set a quit date in two weeks. He is psychiatrically stable, has normal renal function and no history of seizures, and asks for the single most effective medication to help him stop. Which do you prescribe?","options":["Varenicline","Bupropion","Naltrexone","Atomoxetine"],"answer":"Varenicline","explanation":"Varenicline, an α4β2 nicotinic partial agonist started about a week before the quit date, is the most effective single pharmacotherapy for smoking cessation; it is renally cleared and essentially free of CYP interactions with his stimulant, with nausea and vivid dreams as the hallmark side effects. Bupropion is an approved but less effective cessation aid that also lowers the seizure threshold, naltrexone treats alcohol and opioid use disorder, and atomoxetine has no role in smoking cessation.","meds":["varenicline","bupropion","naltrexone","atomoxetine","lisdexamfetamine"],"disorder":"Tobacco use disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["first-line","substance","comorbidity"],"source":{"name":"Varenicline monograph / deck pearls — smoking cessation efficacy","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_ad_mdd_tamoxifen_cyp2d6","stem":"A 52-year-old woman is taking tamoxifen after breast-cancer surgery and develops a moderate major depressive episode. Tamoxifen requires CYP2D6 activation to endoxifen, so a strong CYP2D6 inhibitor must be avoided. Which antidepressant is the most appropriate choice?","options":["Escitalopram","Paroxetine","Fluoxetine","Bupropion"],"answer":"Escitalopram","explanation":"Escitalopram is metabolized mainly by CYP2C19 and causes minimal CYP inhibition, so it does not meaningfully impair tamoxifen activation. Paroxetine is a potent CYP2D6 inhibitor explicitly flagged as an avoid-with-tamoxifen combination, fluoxetine is likewise a potent 2D6 inhibitor, and bupropion (with its hydroxybupropion metabolite) is also a potent 2D6 inhibitor that lowers tamoxifen activation.","meds":["escitalopram","paroxetine","fluoxetine","bupropion"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":3,"tags":["interaction","cyp2d6","oncology"],"source":{"name":"Product monographs — CYP2D6 inhibition (paroxetine, fluoxetine, bupropion)","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ad_mdd_adjunct_aripiprazole","stem":"A 44-year-old with major depressive disorder has only a partial response after 8 weeks of escitalopram 20 mg/day with confirmed adherence. You elect to augment rather than switch. Which agent carries a Health Canada indication for adjunctive treatment of major depressive disorder?","options":["Aripiprazole","Haloperidol","Loxapine","Chlorpromazine"],"answer":"Aripiprazole","explanation":"Aripiprazole is approved in Canada as adjunctive treatment of MDD and is used at low adjunct doses (2–5 mg/day); counsel about akathisia and about impulse-control urges (gambling, hypersexuality, compulsive shopping/eating). Haloperidol, loxapine and chlorpromazine are first-generation antipsychotics with no adjunctive MDD indication and greater EPS, sedation and anticholinergic burden.","meds":["aripiprazole","escitalopram","haloperidol","loxapine","chlorpromazine"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["augmentation","canmat"],"source":{"name":"Health Canada indication — aripiprazole adjunctive MDD; CANMAT 2016 MDD","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vd_ad_mdd_sexual_dysfunction_switch","stem":"A 34-year-old man is in remission from major depression on sertraline but has distressing anorgasmia and low libido and wants to switch. He has a history of bulimia nervosa, so bupropion is contraindicated. Which switch best preserves antidepressant efficacy with a lower rate of sexual dysfunction?","options":["Vortioxetine","Paroxetine","Venlafaxine","Fluvoxamine"],"answer":"Vortioxetine","explanation":"Vortioxetine is a multimodal serotonergic agent approved for MDD whose rate of sexual dysfunction is lower than that of the SSRIs (its dominant, dose-dependent side effect is nausea). Paroxetine has the most sexual dysfunction of the SSRIs, and venlafaxine and fluvoxamine both list sexual dysfunction as a common effect; bupropion — normally the classic answer here — is excluded because it is contraindicated in bulimia/anorexia given its seizure risk.","meds":["vortioxetine","sertraline","paroxetine","venlafaxine","fluvoxamine","bupropion"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["sexual-dysfunction","tolerability","switching"],"source":{"name":"Vortioxetine and bupropion product monographs; CANMAT 2016 MDD","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_ad_mdd_discontinuation_syndrome","stem":"A patient who ran out of his antidepressant 48 hours ago presents with dizziness, nausea, irritability, flu-like malaise and electric-shock “brain zaps”. Which of the following agents is the most likely culprit?","options":["Paroxetine","Fluoxetine","Vortioxetine","Mirtazapine"],"answer":"Paroxetine","explanation":"Paroxetine has the worst discontinuation syndrome of the SSRIs: a roughly 21-hour half-life with no clinically significant active metabolite, so levels fall abruptly — always taper slowly. Fluoxetine is effectively self-tapering (norfluoxetine 7–15 days), vortioxetine's ~66-hour half-life makes discontinuation mild, and mirtazapine discontinuation is generally mild as well.","meds":["paroxetine","fluoxetine","vortioxetine","mirtazapine"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["discontinuation","half-life"],"source":{"name":"Paroxetine and fluoxetine product monographs — half-life and discontinuation","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ad_mdd_elderly_recurrent_hyponatremia","stem":"An 81-year-old woman developed symptomatic hyponatremia (Na 122 mmol/L) three weeks after starting citalopram; it resolved on stopping the drug, and a later trial of venlafaxine reproduced it. Her depression has now relapsed and she needs pharmacotherapy. Which antidepressant is least likely to cause SIADH/hyponatremia?","options":["Bupropion","Escitalopram","Duloxetine","Mirtazapine"],"answer":"Bupropion","explanation":"Antidepressant-associated SIADH is essentially a serotonergic class effect, and older women are the highest-risk group; bupropion is a noradrenergic-dopaminergic agent with no direct serotonergic activity and hyponatremia is not among its listed serious adverse effects. Escitalopram, duloxetine and mirtazapine all carry hyponatremia/SIADH warnings and would risk repeating the event.","meds":["bupropion","citalopram","venlafaxine","escitalopram","duloxetine","mirtazapine"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":3,"tags":["hyponatremia","elderly","monitoring"],"source":{"name":"SSRI/SNRI product monographs — hyponatremia/SIADH warnings","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ad_gad_hepatic_avoid_duloxetine","stem":"A 49-year-old man with generalized anxiety disorder drinks 6–8 standard drinks daily and has ALT and AST at three times the upper limit of normal. Which agent should be AVOIDED in this setting?","options":["Duloxetine","Escitalopram","Buspirone","Pregabalin"],"answer":"Duloxetine","explanation":"Despite its Canadian GAD indication, duloxetine carries a hepatotoxicity warning and is specifically avoided in hepatic impairment or substantial alcohol use. Escitalopram remains usable with a reduced ceiling (10 mg/day in hepatic impairment), buspirone is a non-dependence-forming GAD option, and pregabalin is renally cleared with no CYP metabolism — all far safer for this liver.","meds":["duloxetine","escitalopram","buspirone","pregabalin"],"disorder":"Generalized anxiety disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["hepatic","contraindication","alcohol"],"source":{"name":"Duloxetine product monograph — hepatotoxicity warning","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ad_gad_bp_monitoring_titration","stem":"A 45-year-old with generalized anxiety disorder and borderline hypertension is having her medication titrated upward. Which of the following requires a blood-pressure check at every dose increase because its noradrenergic effect — and a sustained diastolic rise — emerges above roughly 150 mg/day?","options":["Venlafaxine","Sertraline","Buspirone","Mirtazapine"],"answer":"Venlafaxine","explanation":"Venlafaxine is serotonergic at low doses but becomes noradrenergic above about 150 mg/day, which is when dose-dependent hypertension appears; check BP at each increase and use caution in uncontrolled hypertension. Sertraline and buspirone do not raise blood pressure, and mirtazapine's problems are sedation, appetite/weight gain and lipids rather than hypertension.","meds":["venlafaxine","sertraline","buspirone","mirtazapine"],"disorder":"Generalized anxiety disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["monitoring","cardiac","dosing"],"source":{"name":"Venlafaxine product monograph — dose-dependent hypertension","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ad_panic_propranolol_asthma","stem":"A 33-year-old woman with panic disorder and moderate persistent asthma (on regular inhaled salbutamol) read that a beta-blocker abolishes palpitations and asks to be prescribed one. Which of the following agents is contraindicated for her?","options":["Propranolol","Sertraline","Escitalopram","Clonazepam"],"answer":"Propranolol","explanation":"Propranolol is non-selective and formally contraindicated in bronchial asthma — it can precipitate bronchospasm and antagonizes her β2-agonist — and in any case it has no role in maintenance treatment of panic disorder (its niche is akathisia, tremor and situational performance anxiety). Sertraline is Health Canada-approved for panic disorder, escitalopram is used off-label, and short-course clonazepam is an approved bridging option.","meds":["propranolol","sertraline","escitalopram","clonazepam"],"disorder":"Panic disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["contraindication","respiratory"],"source":{"name":"Propranolol label — contraindicated in bronchial asthma","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ad_ocd_dose_ceiling_seizure","stem":"A 31-year-old with severe OCD has only a partial response after 12 weeks and asks whether her dose can be pushed higher. Which of the following cannot be titrated beyond 250 mg/day because of dose-dependent seizure risk, and also carries by far the highest overdose lethality of the four?","options":["Clomipramine","Fluvoxamine","Sertraline","Escitalopram"],"answer":"Clomipramine","explanation":"Clomipramine's 250 mg/day ceiling exists because it has the greatest dose-dependent seizure risk of the TCAs, and TCA overdose is potentially lethal through sodium-channel blockade (wide QRS, arrhythmia, coma) — a serious consideration in OCD, which often needs high-dose therapy. The SSRIs are capped for unrelated reasons (fluvoxamine 300 mg/day, sertraline 200 mg/day, escitalopram 20 mg/day) and are comparatively safe in overdose.","meds":["clomipramine","fluvoxamine","sertraline","escitalopram"],"disorder":"Obsessive-compulsive disorder","difficulty":3,"tags":["dosing","seizure","overdose"],"source":{"name":"Clomipramine product monograph — 250 mg/day ceiling, seizure and overdose risk","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ad_ptsd_sleep_onset_adjunct","stem":"A 38-year-old man with PTSD on sertraline 150 mg/day has good daytime improvement and no nightmares, but persistent difficulty initiating sleep. He has alcohol use disorder in sustained remission. Which adjunct is most appropriate?","options":["Trazodone","Zopiclone","Lorazepam","Prazosin"],"answer":"Trazodone","explanation":"Low-dose trazodone is the usual non-dependence-forming sedating adjunct for sleep-onset insomnia alongside an SSRI; counsel men about priapism as a urologic emergency and watch orthostatic hypotension. Zopiclone and lorazepam are dependence-forming and best avoided given his substance-use history, and prazosin targets trauma nightmares — which this patient does not have.","meds":["trazodone","sertraline","zopiclone","lorazepam","prazosin"],"disorder":"Post-traumatic stress disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["insomnia","adjunct","substance-use"],"source":{"name":"Trazodone, zopiclone and prazosin product monographs; Canadian PTSD practice","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_ad_sad_rima_moclobemide","stem":"A 30-year-old with generalized social anxiety disorder has failed adequate trials of paroxetine and then venlafaxine. Which agent carries a Health Canada indication for social anxiety disorder and, being a reversible MAO-A inhibitor, does not require a strict low-tyramine diet?","options":["Moclobemide","Phenelzine","Selegiline","Amitriptyline"],"answer":"Moclobemide","explanation":"Moclobemide is a RIMA approved in Canada for both MDD and social anxiety disorder; because tyramine can displace it from MAO-A, no strict diet is required — but its serotonin-syndrome contraindications are unchanged, so allow a washout (about a week after venlafaxine, five weeks after fluoxetine) before starting it. Phenelzine has social-anxiety evidence but is irreversible and mandates a strict tyramine diet with a 14-day washout, selegiline is approved in Canada only for Parkinson's disease, and amitriptyline has no social-anxiety role.","meds":["moclobemide","phenelzine","selegiline","amitriptyline","paroxetine","venlafaxine"],"disorder":"Social anxiety disorder","difficulty":3,"tags":["maoi","rima","washout"],"source":{"name":"Moclobemide (Manerix) Canadian monograph — SAD indication, reversible MAO-A inhibition","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_ad_ss_linezolid_ssri","stem":"A 58-year-old maintained on escitalopram is admitted with MRSA bacteremia and started on linezolid. Thirty-six hours later he is agitated and diaphoretic with a temperature of 38.6°C, dilated pupils, brisk reflexes and inducible clonus that is far more marked in the legs than the arms. What is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Serotonin syndrome","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Hypertensive crisis (tyramine reaction)","Anticholinergic toxicity"],"answer":"Serotonin syndrome","explanation":"Linezolid is a monoamine oxidase inhibitor and SSRI labels list it as a contraindicated combination; onset within hours to a day with clonus, hyperreflexia, mydriasis and lower-limb predominance is classic serotonin toxicity — stop the serotonergic agents and give supportive care with benzodiazepines. NMS evolves over days after dopamine blockade with lead-pipe rigidity and hyporeflexia, a tyramine reaction requires an MAOI plus a tyramine load and causes hypertension without clonus, and anticholinergic toxicity gives dry flushed skin, absent bowel sounds and normal reflexes.","meds":["escitalopram"],"disorder":"Serotonin syndrome","difficulty":2,"tags":["serotonin","interaction"],"source":{"name":"SSRI product monographs — linezolid/MAOI contraindication","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ad_maoi_sympathomimetic_crisis","stem":"A 46-year-old on tranylcypromine for treatment-resistant depression takes an over-the-counter cold remedy containing pseudoephedrine. Within an hour he has a pounding occipital headache, neck stiffness, palpitations and a blood pressure of 220/125 mmHg. He is alert and oriented, with no rigidity and no clonus. What is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Hypertensive crisis (MAOI–sympathomimetic reaction)","Serotonin syndrome","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Anticholinergic toxicity"],"answer":"Hypertensive crisis (MAOI–sympathomimetic reaction)","explanation":"Irreversible MAOIs prevent breakdown of indirect sympathomimetics such as pseudoephedrine, producing the same adrenergic crisis as a tyramine load — occipital headache, severe hypertension and palpitations, with a risk of intracranial hemorrhage; patients on tranylcypromine or phenelzine must avoid all decongestants, and the restriction persists about two weeks after stopping. Serotonin syndrome requires a serotonergic co-ingestant and shows clonus and hyperreflexia, NMS follows dopamine blockade with rigidity and fever over days, and anticholinergic toxicity causes delirium with dry flushed skin rather than this degree of hypertension.","meds":["tranylcypromine"],"disorder":"Hypertensive crisis (tyramine reaction)","difficulty":3,"tags":["maoi","hypertensive-crisis","interaction"],"source":{"name":"Tranylcypromine label — sympathomimetics and hypertensive crisis","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ap_scz_ziprasidone_food_absorption","stem":"A 27-year-old man with schizophrenia was switched to ziprasidone to avoid further weight gain. Eight weeks later his positive symptoms are unchanged; pill counts and a pharmacy profile confirm adherence, but he takes both doses on an empty stomach because food 'makes him feel worse'. Which antipsychotic's bioavailability falls by roughly half when it is not taken with a meal of at least 500 kcal?","options":["Ziprasidone","Aripiprazole","Risperidone","Quetiapine"],"answer":"Ziprasidone","explanation":"Ziprasidone absorption roughly doubles with a ≥500 kcal meal, so empty-stomach dosing is a classic cause of apparent treatment failure — the correction is food, not dose escalation. Aripiprazole and risperidone may be taken with or without food, and quetiapine's only food caveat is that the XR form should be taken without food or with a light meal.","meds":["ziprasidone","aripiprazole","risperidone","quetiapine"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":2,"tags":["pharmacokinetics","adherence","metabolic"],"source":{"name":"Ziprasidone monograph (food effect)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_ap_scz_clozapine_ileus_anticholinergic","stem":"A 38-year-old on clozapine 400 mg/day for treatment-resistant schizophrenia has had no bowel movement for six days and now has abdominal distension, vomiting and absent bowel sounds. His neutrophil count is normal and he is afebrile. Which co-prescribed medication most likely contributed to this potentially fatal complication?","options":["Benztropine","Propranolol","Lorazepam","Amantadine"],"answer":"Benztropine","explanation":"Clozapine causes severe gastrointestinal hypomotility that can progress to paralytic ileus or bowel obstruction and be fatal, and anticholinergics compound it — paralytic ileus is itself a listed serious adverse effect of benztropine. Propranolol, lorazepam and amantadine carry no comparable antimuscarinic bowel risk; prophylactic laxatives and active bowel monitoring are standard clozapine care.","meds":["clozapine","benztropine","propranolol","lorazepam","amantadine"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":3,"tags":["clozapine","interaction","monitoring"],"source":{"name":"Clozapine label — GI hypomotility warning","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ap_scz_lai_oral_overlap","stem":"A 31-year-old with schizophrenia stabilized on oral risperidone is started on a long-acting injectable to support adherence, and the team asks how long to continue the oral medication. Which long-acting injectable is the exception in requiring roughly three weeks of continued oral antipsychotic coverage after the first injection?","options":["Risperidone","Paliperidone","Haloperidol","Flupenthixol"],"answer":"Risperidone","explanation":"Risperidone LAI (Consta) has a ~3-week lag before meaningful drug release, so oral risperidone must be continued through that window — it is the exception among depots. Paliperidone palmitate does not need a 3-week oral overlap, and the decanoates (haloperidol, flupenthixol) are covered by a shorter oral overlap until steady state is reached.","meds":["risperidone","paliperidone","haloperidol","flupenthixol"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":3,"tags":["lai","switching","adherence"],"source":{"name":"Risperidone / paliperidone monographs (LAI initiation)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_ap_scz_impulse_control_monitoring","stem":"A 34-year-old with schizophrenia, psychiatrically stable for a year, has quietly accumulated large gambling debts and reports new compulsive shopping and hypersexuality that began after his antipsychotic was started. Which agent carries a specific warning for these urges, such that they should be asked about at every visit?","options":["Aripiprazole","Haloperidol","Quetiapine","Ziprasidone"],"answer":"Aripiprazole","explanation":"Dopamine partial agonists — aripiprazole, and as a class effect brexpiprazole — carry an impulse-control warning covering pathological gambling, hypersexuality, compulsive shopping and binge eating, so monitoring means specifically asking about these urges. Haloperidol, quetiapine and ziprasidone are D2 antagonists and do not carry this warning.","meds":["aripiprazole","haloperidol","quetiapine","ziprasidone","brexpiprazole"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":2,"tags":["monitoring","impulse-control"],"source":{"name":"Aripiprazole monograph (impulse-control warning)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_ap_agit_inhaled_loxapine","stem":"A cooperative but escalating patient with psychotic agitation in a supervised clinic setting refuses an intramuscular injection. He has no asthma or COPD and a rescue bronchodilator is available. Which agent offers a rapid single-dose INHALED route for acute agitation?","options":["Loxapine","Perphenazine","Pimozide","Trifluoperazine"],"answer":"Loxapine","explanation":"Loxapine's inhaled formulation gives rapid, single-dose control of acute agitation in a supervised setting — but it can cause bronchospasm, so it is contraindicated in asthma/COPD and a rescue bronchodilator must be on hand. Perphenazine, pimozide and trifluoperazine are oral agents with no rapid-onset inhaled option.","meds":["loxapine","perphenazine","pimozide","trifluoperazine"],"disorder":"Acute agitation","difficulty":2,"tags":["agitation","formulation"],"source":{"name":"Loxapine monograph (inhaled formulation)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_ap_agit_zuclopenthixol_acetate","stem":"An inpatient with acute psychotic disturbance has required repeated intramuscular injections over 24 hours. The team wants a single intramuscular dose that will cover roughly the next two to three days while an oral regimen is established — explicitly not a maintenance depot. Which Canadian agent has a short-acting ACETATE ester for this purpose?","options":["Zuclopenthixol","Pipotiazine","Fluphenazine","Paliperidone"],"answer":"Zuclopenthixol","explanation":"Zuclopenthixol acetate (Acuphase) is a short-acting intramuscular ester bridging roughly 72 hours of acute disturbance; the same molecule's decanoate is the maintenance depot, and confusing the two esters is the classic error. Pipotiazine palmitate, fluphenazine decanoate and paliperidone palmitate are all long-acting maintenance injectables that cannot be quickly withdrawn if poorly tolerated.","meds":["zuclopenthixol","pipotiazine","fluphenazine","paliperidone"],"disorder":"Acute agitation","difficulty":3,"tags":["agitation","lai","canada"],"source":{"name":"Zuclopenthixol monograph (acetate vs decanoate)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_ap_delirium_qt_droperidol","stem":"A 71-year-old in the intensive care unit has hyperactive delirium requiring pharmacologic control. His QTc is 510 ms, potassium is 3.1 mmol/L, and he is already receiving other QT-prolonging medications. Which agent is most important to AVOID because torsades de pointes is its defining hazard, reported even at low antiemetic doses?","options":["Droperidol","Aripiprazole","Loxapine","Olanzapine"],"answer":"Droperidol","explanation":"Droperidol carries a prominent dose-dependent QT/torsades warning that applies even at low antiemetic doses, making it the wrong choice with a QTc of 510 ms and hypokalemia — correct potassium and magnesium first. Aripiprazole is essentially QT-neutral and loxapine and olanzapine carry a far weaker QT signal, though any antipsychotic warrants caution in this setting.","meds":["droperidol","aripiprazole","loxapine","olanzapine"],"disorder":"Delirium","difficulty":2,"tags":["qt","delirium","elderly"],"source":{"name":"Droperidol monograph (QT/torsades warning)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_ap_delirium_anticholinergic_toxidrome","stem":"An 80-year-old receiving low-dose haloperidol for post-operative delirium has benztropine added for tremor. Two days later he is agitated and hallucinating, with dry flushed skin, dilated pupils, urinary retention, a temperature of 38.4°C and tachycardia. Muscle tone is normal, there is no clonus, and creatine kinase is normal. Which syndrome is this?","options":["Anticholinergic toxicity","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Serotonin syndrome","Catatonia"],"answer":"Anticholinergic toxicity","explanation":"Delirium with dry flushed skin, mydriasis, urinary retention and hyperthermia from impaired sweating — with NORMAL tone and a normal CK — is the anticholinergic toxidrome; anticholinergic delirium and heat stroke are listed serious adverse effects of benztropine. NMS would show lead-pipe rigidity with a markedly raised CK, serotonin syndrome clonus and hyperreflexia, and catatonia immobility with waxy flexibility rather than this autonomic picture.","meds":["benztropine","haloperidol"],"disorder":"Delirium","difficulty":2,"tags":["syndrome-id","anticholinergic","elderly"],"source":{"name":"Benztropine monograph (anticholinergic delirium)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_ap_pdp_quetiapine_canada","stem":"A 76-year-old with Parkinson disease has distressing visual hallucinations. Medical precipitants have been treated and his dopaminergic therapy is already minimized, so an antipsychotic is needed — but pimavanserin is not marketed in Canada. Which agent is the usual Canadian choice because its loose, low-occupancy D2 binding makes it least likely to worsen his motor symptoms?","options":["Quetiapine","Risperidone","Haloperidol","Zuclopenthixol"],"answer":"Quetiapine","explanation":"Quetiapine has the lowest EPS and prolactin burden of the standard agents because of its loose D2 binding, which is why it is the Canadian go-to for Parkinson disease psychosis (clozapine, which is also used off-label here, is the alternative when its monitoring is feasible). Risperidone is the most D2-potent SGA, and haloperidol and zuclopenthixol are high-potency D2 blockers that will aggravate parkinsonism.","meds":["quetiapine","risperidone","haloperidol","zuclopenthixol","clozapine","pimavanserin"],"disorder":"Parkinson disease psychosis","difficulty":2,"tags":["pd-psychosis","eps","canada"],"source":{"name":"Quetiapine / clozapine monographs","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_ap_dementia_brexpiprazole_agitation","stem":"An 81-year-old with Alzheimer disease has persistent agitation despite optimized non-pharmacologic management. His daughter has read about a newer dopamine partial agonist that is approved in the United States specifically for agitation associated with Alzheimer dementia and asks whether it is an option. Which agent is she describing?","options":["Brexpiprazole","Chlorpromazine","Pimozide","Trifluoperazine"],"answer":"Brexpiprazole","explanation":"Brexpiprazole, a D2/5-HT1A partial agonist, is approved in some jurisdictions (US) for agitation associated with dementia — it is not a Canadian indication, and like every antipsychotic it carries the warning of increased mortality and cerebrovascular events in elderly patients with dementia. Chlorpromazine, pimozide and trifluoperazine are older agents whose sedation, anticholinergic and orthostatic load, and QT risk make them poor choices in this population.","meds":["brexpiprazole","chlorpromazine","pimozide","trifluoperazine"],"disorder":"Major neurocognitive disorder (dementia)","difficulty":3,"tags":["bpsd","elderly"],"source":{"name":"Brexpiprazole monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_ap_nms_amantadine_withdrawal","stem":"A 62-year-old on long-term haloperidol at an unchanged dose has been taking amantadine for drug-induced parkinsonism. On admission for pneumonia the amantadine is abruptly stopped. Within 48 hours he is febrile and rigid with fluctuating consciousness, labile blood pressure and a creatine kinase of 6000 U/L. What has happened?","options":["Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Serotonin syndrome","Anticholinergic toxicity","Catatonia"],"answer":"Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","explanation":"Abruptly withdrawing a dopaminergic agent such as amantadine can precipitate an NMS-like syndrome — hyperthermia, rigidity, altered mental status, autonomic instability and rhabdomyolysis — even with no change in antipsychotic dose, which is why amantadine should be tapered rather than stopped. Serotonin syndrome gives clonus and hyperreflexia, anticholinergic toxicity dry flushed skin with normal tone and CK, and catatonia immobility without autonomic collapse or a raised CK.","meds":["amantadine","haloperidol"],"disorder":"Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","difficulty":3,"tags":["nms","syndrome-id","withdrawal"],"source":{"name":"Amantadine monograph (NMS-like withdrawal syndrome)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_ap_eps_antiemetic_dystonia","stem":"A 22-year-old woman given an intramuscular antiemetic in the emergency department for vomiting returns four hours later with painful neck twisting, jaw stiffness and an upward fixed gaze. She takes no psychiatric medication and has never received an antipsychotic. Which drug is responsible?","options":["Prochlorperazine","Hydroxyzine","Lorazepam","Propranolol"],"answer":"Prochlorperazine","explanation":"Prochlorperazine is a dopamine-blocking phenothiazine used mainly as an antiemetic, and a single 'just an antiemetic' dose can precipitate acute dystonia — classically in young patients — which is treated with an anticholinergic such as benztropine. Hydroxyzine, lorazepam and propranolol do not block D2 receptors and do not cause dystonic reactions.","meds":["prochlorperazine","hydroxyzine","lorazepam","propranolol","benztropine"],"disorder":"Extrapyramidal symptoms","difficulty":2,"tags":["eps","dystonia"],"source":{"name":"Prochlorperazine monograph (acute dystonic reaction)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_ap_td_vmat2_depression_risk","stem":"A 59-year-old with schizophrenia has troublesome tardive dyskinesia and is simultaneously in an active major depressive episode with passive suicidal ideation. Valbenazine and deutetrabenazine are not marketed in Canada. Which of the following options carries a dopamine-depletion risk of worsening depression and suicidality that makes it hazardous in this particular patient?","options":["Tetrabenazine","Propranolol","Clozapine","Amantadine"],"answer":"Tetrabenazine","explanation":"Tetrabenazine is the Canada-available VMAT2 inhibitor for tardive dyskinesia, but because it depletes dopamine its serious adverse effects include depression and suicidality (plus parkinsonism), so mood must be screened and it is avoided during an active depressive episode. Switching the offending antipsychotic to clozapine (essentially no EPS from its loose D2 binding) or using amantadine as a tardive-dyskinesia adjunct are safer routes here, while propranolol treats akathisia rather than tardive dyskinesia.","meds":["tetrabenazine","propranolol","clozapine","amantadine","valbenazine","deutetrabenazine"],"disorder":"Tardive dyskinesia","difficulty":3,"tags":["tardive-dyskinesia","safety"],"source":{"name":"Tetrabenazine monograph (depression/suicidality)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"va_anx_gad_firstline_1","stem":"A 29-year-old with generalized anxiety disorder and no comorbidities has never been treated. You want a CANMAT/Canadian-guideline first-line agent that is also Health Canada-approved for GAD, well tolerated, and has a clean interaction profile. Best initial choice?","options":["Escitalopram","Bupropion","Clonazepam","Amitriptyline"],"answer":"Escitalopram","explanation":"Escitalopram is first-line and approved for GAD with the cleanest interaction profile of the SSRIs. Bupropion has no anxiety indication (and can be activating); benzodiazepines are not first-line maintenance; TCAs are later-line and poorly tolerated.","meds":["escitalopram","bupropion","clonazepam","amitriptyline"],"disorder":"Generalized anxiety disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line","canmat"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014; CANMAT","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_anx_gad_buspirone_aug_2","stem":"A patient with generalized anxiety disorder has a partial response after an adequate trial of escitalopram. She previously became dependent on a benzodiazepine and wants an augmenting agent with no abuse liability and no sedation. Which is the best add-on?","options":["Buspirone","Alprazolam","Lorazepam","Diazepam"],"answer":"Buspirone","explanation":"Buspirone is a 5-HT1A partial agonist approved for GAD and used to augment SSRIs; it has no dependence liability and no sedation, but a delayed (1–2 week) onset. Alprazolam, lorazepam, and diazepam are all benzodiazepines carrying exactly the dependence risk she wants to avoid.","meds":["buspirone","alprazolam","lorazepam","diazepam"],"disorder":"Generalized anxiety disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["augmentation"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014; buspirone monograph","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_anx_gad_elderly_avoid_benzo_3","stem":"A 76-year-old with generalized anxiety disorder, a prior fall, and mild renal impairment needs pharmacotherapy. You want durable maintenance efficacy while minimizing falls, sedation, and dependence. Which agent best fits?","options":["Diazepam","Alprazolam","Duloxetine","Lorazepam"],"answer":"Duloxetine","explanation":"Duloxetine is approved for GAD and is an appropriate first-line maintenance option; benzodiazepines are relatively contraindicated in older adults (Beers criteria) because of falls, sedation, cognitive impairment, and dependence. Long-acting diazepam is especially problematic given accumulation in the elderly.","meds":["duloxetine","diazepam","alprazolam","lorazepam"],"disorder":"Generalized anxiety disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["elderly","avoidance"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014; Beers criteria","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_anx_gad_pregabalin_4","stem":"A patient with generalized anxiety disorder cannot tolerate SSRIs or SNRIs (repeated nausea and sexual dysfunction) and refuses ongoing benzodiazepines. You want a non-benzodiazepine agent with randomized-trial evidence and relatively rapid onset in GAD. Which is most appropriate?","options":["Pregabalin","Alprazolam","Bupropion","Clonazepam"],"answer":"Pregabalin","explanation":"Pregabalin has robust RCT evidence in GAD (approved for GAD in Europe; used off-label in Canada), with a relatively fast onset and no serotonergic side effects. Alprazolam and clonazepam are benzodiazepines the patient declined; bupropion has no anxiety efficacy.","meds":["pregabalin","alprazolam","bupropion","clonazepam"],"disorder":"Generalized anxiety disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["first-line"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014; pregabalin GAD RCTs","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_anx_panic_firstline_startlow_5","stem":"A 34-year-old with panic disorder is very sensitive to somatic sensations and fears medication side effects. You choose an SSRI approved for panic disorder and plan to start at half the usual dose (25 mg) to avoid early activation/jitteriness. Which agent are you describing?","options":["Sertraline","Bupropion","Phenelzine","Amitriptyline"],"answer":"Sertraline","explanation":"Sertraline is first-line and approved for panic disorder; the standard is to start at 25 mg (half-dose) and go slow to avoid the initial activation that can be mistaken for panic. Bupropion is activating and not indicated; MAOIs/TCAs are later-line reserved options.","meds":["sertraline","bupropion","phenelzine","amitriptyline"],"disorder":"Panic disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line","start-low"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014; sertraline monograph","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_anx_panic_benzo_bridge_6","stem":"A patient with severe, frequent panic attacks is starting an SSRI, but you want a short-term benzodiazepine bridge for the first few weeks. You prefer an agent whose longer half-life gives smoother coverage and less inter-dose rebound anxiety. Which benzodiazepine best fits a panic bridge?","options":["Clonazepam","Alprazolam","Lorazepam","Oxazepam"],"answer":"Clonazepam","explanation":"Clonazepam is long-acting and approved for panic disorder, giving smoother coverage with less inter-dose rebound than short-acting agents. Alprazolam and lorazepam are short-acting and prone to inter-dose rebound and dependence; oxazepam is short-acting and not used for panic bridging.","meds":["clonazepam","alprazolam","lorazepam","oxazepam"],"disorder":"Panic disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["bridging"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014; clonazepam monograph","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_anx_panic_switch_snri_7","stem":"A patient with panic disorder has an inadequate response to paroxetine and you elect to switch to an SNRI that is Health Canada-approved specifically for panic disorder. Which agent qualifies?","options":["Venlafaxine","Duloxetine","Desvenlafaxine","Bupropion"],"answer":"Venlafaxine","explanation":"Venlafaxine (XR) is approved for panic disorder and is an evidence-based next step after an SSRI. Duloxetine is approved for GAD but not panic; desvenlafaxine is approved only for MDD; bupropion is not an anxiolytic. Cross-taper and watch for early activation.","meds":["venlafaxine","duloxetine","desvenlafaxine","bupropion"],"disorder":"Panic disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["switching","first-line"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014; venlafaxine monograph","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_anx_ocd_firstline_dosing_8","stem":"A 24-year-old with obsessive-compulsive disorder is starting pharmacotherapy. You counsel that OCD typically needs higher SSRI doses and a longer trial (10–12 weeks) than depression. Which agent is an appropriate guideline first-line SSRI for OCD?","options":["Fluvoxamine","Bupropion","Nortriptyline","Amitriptyline"],"answer":"Fluvoxamine","explanation":"Fluvoxamine is a first-line SSRI approved for OCD; OCD requires higher doses and longer trials than MDD. Bupropion has no OCD efficacy, and TCAs other than clomipramine (e.g., nortriptyline, amitriptyline) are ineffective because they lack strong serotonergic activity.","meds":["fluvoxamine","bupropion","nortriptyline","amitriptyline"],"disorder":"Obsessive-compulsive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["first-line","monitoring"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014 (OCD)","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_anx_ocd_clomipramine_9","stem":"A patient with obsessive-compulsive disorder has failed adequate high-dose trials of two SSRIs. You consider the one tricyclic with proven OCD efficacy, noting its dose is capped at 250 mg/day because of dose-dependent seizure risk. Which agent is it?","options":["Clomipramine","Amitriptyline","Nortriptyline","Desipramine"],"answer":"Clomipramine","explanation":"Clomipramine is the strongly serotonergic TCA approved for OCD and effective when SSRIs fail; its ceiling of 250 mg/day is driven by dose-dependent seizure risk. The noradrenergic TCAs (amitriptyline, nortriptyline, desipramine) are not effective in OCD.","meds":["clomipramine","amitriptyline","nortriptyline","desipramine"],"disorder":"Obsessive-compulsive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["switching","overdose"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014 (OCD); clomipramine monograph","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_anx_ocd_antipsychotic_aug_10","stem":"A patient with obsessive-compulsive disorder has only a partial response after an adequate high-dose SSRI trial plus CBT with exposure and response prevention. What is the best-evidenced pharmacologic augmentation strategy?","options":["Risperidone","Buspirone","Lorazepam","Mirtazapine"],"answer":"Risperidone","explanation":"Low-dose antipsychotic augmentation (e.g., risperidone) is the evidence-based next step for SSRI-refractory OCD. Buspirone augmentation is not effective in OCD, benzodiazepines do not treat the core illness, and mirtazapine lacks OCD augmentation evidence.","meds":["risperidone","buspirone","lorazepam","mirtazapine"],"disorder":"Obsessive-compulsive disorder","difficulty":3,"tags":["augmentation"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014 (OCD augmentation)","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_anx_ptsd_firstline_11","stem":"A 40-year-old veteran with post-traumatic stress disorder is starting pharmacotherapy. Which agent is Health Canada-approved and first-line for PTSD?","options":["Sertraline","Diazepam","Bupropion","Alprazolam"],"answer":"Sertraline","explanation":"Sertraline is approved and first-line for PTSD (SSRIs/SNRIs are the mainstay). Benzodiazepines such as diazepam and alprazolam are not recommended in PTSD—they do not treat core symptoms and may impair fear extinction—and bupropion has no PTSD efficacy.","meds":["sertraline","diazepam","bupropion","alprazolam"],"disorder":"Post-traumatic stress disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014 (PTSD); sertraline monograph","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_anx_ptsd_prazosin_nightmares_12","stem":"A patient with post-traumatic stress disorder has good daytime improvement on paroxetine but persistent trauma-related nightmares and sleep disruption. You add a targeted agent at 1 mg at bedtime and warn about first-dose orthostatic hypotension. Which drug is this?","options":["Prazosin","Clonazepam","Quetiapine","Zopiclone"],"answer":"Prazosin","explanation":"Prazosin, an α1-antagonist, is used off-label for PTSD nightmares, started at 1 mg at bedtime with counseling about first-dose orthostasis. Clonazepam is a benzodiazepine (avoided in PTSD), and quetiapine and zopiclone are not the targeted evidence-based choice for trauma nightmares.","meds":["prazosin","clonazepam","quetiapine","zopiclone"],"disorder":"Post-traumatic stress disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["monitoring"],"source":{"name":"Prazosin PTSD-nightmares literature; prazosin monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"va_anx_ptsd_avoid_benzo_13","stem":"A patient with post-traumatic stress disorder and prominent anxiety asks specifically for ongoing lorazepam. You explain that benzodiazepines are not recommended in PTSD (they can worsen outcomes and impair trauma processing) and instead start an approved first-line agent. Which do you choose?","options":["Lorazepam","Diazepam","Paroxetine","Alprazolam"],"answer":"Paroxetine","explanation":"Paroxetine is approved and first-line for PTSD. Benzodiazepines (lorazepam, diazepam, alprazolam) are not recommended in PTSD—they fail to treat core symptoms, may impair fear extinction, and carry dependence and disinhibition risks.","meds":["paroxetine","lorazepam","diazepam","alprazolam"],"disorder":"Post-traumatic stress disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["avoidance","first-line"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014 (PTSD); paroxetine monograph","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_anx_sad_generalized_firstline_14","stem":"A 27-year-old with generalized social anxiety disorder avoids meetings, dating, and phone calls across nearly all social situations. Which is an appropriate Health Canada-approved first-line agent for generalized social anxiety disorder?","options":["Paroxetine","Propranolol","Bupropion","Hydroxyzine"],"answer":"Paroxetine","explanation":"Paroxetine is approved and first-line for generalized social anxiety disorder (SSRIs/SNRIs are the mainstay). Propranolol helps only performance-limited (non-generalized) SAD, bupropion has no SAD evidence, and hydroxyzine is not a first-line SAD treatment.","meds":["paroxetine","propranolol","bupropion","hydroxyzine"],"disorder":"Social anxiety disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014 (SAD); paroxetine monograph","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_anx_sad_performance_betablocker_15","stem":"A professional violinist has intense anxiety, tremor, and palpitations only when performing on stage, with no anxiety in other social situations. She wants an as-needed agent taken shortly before performances. Which is most appropriate?","options":["Propranolol","Sertraline","Clonazepam","Escitalopram"],"answer":"Propranolol","explanation":"Performance-only (non-generalized) social anxiety is best treated with a PRN beta-blocker such as propranolol (10–40 mg ~30–60 min before the event) to blunt autonomic symptoms. A daily SSRI is unnecessary for isolated performance anxiety, and benzodiazepines are avoided given sedation/dependence.","meds":["propranolol","sertraline","clonazepam","escitalopram"],"disorder":"Social anxiety disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014 (performance anxiety); propranolol monograph","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_anx_sad_avoid_benzo_switch_16","stem":"A patient with generalized social anxiety disorder has been maintained on chronic clonazepam by a previous prescriber, with escalating dose and dependence concerns. You want to transition to a sustainable, approved maintenance agent while tapering the benzodiazepine. Which is the best choice?","options":["Venlafaxine","Alprazolam","Diazepam","Lorazepam"],"answer":"Venlafaxine","explanation":"Venlafaxine (XR) is approved for social anxiety disorder and is an appropriate maintenance treatment while the benzodiazepine is slowly tapered. Switching to another benzodiazepine (alprazolam, diazepam, lorazepam) simply perpetuates dependence rather than treating the disorder.","meds":["venlafaxine","alprazolam","diazepam","lorazepam"],"disorder":"Social anxiety disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["switching","avoidance"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014 (SAD); venlafaxine monograph","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_mgmt_oud_first_line_bupnal","stem":"A 29-year-old with opioid use disorder (fentanyl) presents in objective withdrawal (COWS 14) wanting to start opioid agonist therapy. He has young children at home and no significant cardiac history. Which is the best first-line agent?","options":["Buprenorphine / Naloxone","Methadone","Naltrexone","Naloxone"],"answer":"Buprenorphine / Naloxone","explanation":"CRISM guidance favours buprenorphine/naloxone as first-line OAT over methadone for most patients because the partial agonist has a ceiling on respiratory depression (safer in overdose and with take-home doses around children). Methadone is a full agonist with no respiratory ceiling and delayed accumulation; naltrexone is an antagonist that would precipitate withdrawal in an actively dependent patient; naloxone is a short-acting rescue antidote, not maintenance therapy.","meds":["buprenorphine_naloxone","methadone","naltrexone","naloxone"],"disorder":"Opioid use disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line","oud","overdose"],"source":{"name":"CRISM National OUD Guideline","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vx_mgmt_oud_switch_methadone","stem":"A 41-year-old with severe, long-standing opioid use disorder has twice been inducted onto buprenorphine/naloxone but each time developed precipitated withdrawal and left care; he continues to use high-potency opioids daily. His ECG is normal. What is the most appropriate next-step pharmacotherapy?","options":["Methadone","Naltrexone","Naloxone","Acamprosate"],"answer":"Methadone","explanation":"For severe OUD with high tolerance and buprenorphine-induction failure, methadone (a full mu agonist) improves retention and avoids the high-affinity displacement that drives buprenorphine-precipitated withdrawal — accepting the trade-off of no respiratory ceiling and dose-dependent QT, so start low/go slow and monitor ECG. Naltrexone would precipitate withdrawal in an actively dependent patient; naloxone is an overdose antidote; acamprosate treats alcohol, not opioid, use disorder.","meds":["methadone","naltrexone","naloxone","acamprosate"],"disorder":"Opioid use disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["switching","oud","qt"],"source":{"name":"CRISM National OUD Guideline","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vx_mgmt_aud_hepatic_acamprosate","stem":"A 58-year-old with alcohol use disorder and Child-Pugh B alcoholic cirrhosis has been abstinent for 10 days after inpatient withdrawal management and wants a medication to maintain abstinence. Renal function is normal. Which agent is the best choice?","options":["Acamprosate","Naltrexone","Disulfiram","Gabapentin"],"answer":"Acamprosate","explanation":"Acamprosate is renally excreted unchanged and not hepatically metabolized, making it the preferred anti-relapse agent in significant liver disease, and it works best in patients who are already abstinent. Naltrexone and disulfiram are both hepatotoxic and best avoided in decompensated cirrhosis; gabapentin is only an adjunct with weaker evidence, not a first-line maintenance agent here.","meds":["acamprosate","naltrexone","disulfiram","gabapentin"],"disorder":"Alcohol use disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["hepatic","aud"],"source":{"name":"Acamprosate product monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_mgmt_aud_disulfiram_motivated","stem":"A 47-year-old airline pilot with alcohol use disorder is currently abstinent, highly motivated, insightful, and specifically wants a medication that will strongly deter any drinking. He has relapsed despite anti-craving therapy, has normal LFTs and no cardiac disease, and is not taking metronidazole. Which agent best fits his goal?","options":["Disulfiram","Acamprosate","Naltrexone","Topiramate"],"answer":"Disulfiram","explanation":"Disulfiram is an aversive (not anti-craving) agent reserved for motivated, insightful, abstinent patients who want a deterrent — it fits this supervised, high-stakes scenario despite being later-line. Acamprosate and naltrexone reduce craving/relapse but provide no aversive deterrent; topiramate is only an off-label option. Counsel to avoid all hidden alcohol (mouthwash, sauces) and metronidazole, and monitor LFTs.","meds":["disulfiram","acamprosate","naltrexone","topiramate"],"disorder":"Alcohol use disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["aud","switching"],"source":{"name":"Disulfiram product monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_mgmt_tobacco_first_line_varenicline","stem":"A 52-year-old smoker (25 pack-years) with no active psychiatric illness wants the single most effective pharmacotherapy to help him quit. Renal function is normal. Which agent should you recommend?","options":["Varenicline","Bupropion","Nortriptyline","Clonidine"],"answer":"Varenicline","explanation":"Varenicline, an α4β2 nicotinic partial agonist, is the most effective single pharmacotherapy for smoking cessation; start about one week before the quit date and counsel about nausea and vivid dreams. Bupropion and nortriptyline are effective but less so as monotherapy, and clonidine is only a second-line option limited by sedation and hypotension.","meds":["varenicline","bupropion","nortriptyline","clonidine"],"disorder":"Tobacco use disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line","tobacco"],"source":{"name":"EAGLES / Varenicline label","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vx_mgmt_tobacco_comorbid_depression_bupropion","stem":"A 38-year-old smoker also has a new, untreated moderate major depressive episode and wants to stop smoking. She has no seizure history and no eating disorder. If you could choose a single agent to address both problems, which is best?","options":["Bupropion","Varenicline","Nortriptyline","Naltrexone"],"answer":"Bupropion","explanation":"Bupropion is both an antidepressant and an approved smoking-cessation aid (Zyban), so a single agent can treat the depression and support cessation. Varenicline is the most effective cessation drug but does not treat depression; nortriptyline is an aversively toxic later-line antidepressant/cessation aid; naltrexone targets alcohol/opioid use, not nicotine or mood. Avoid bupropion where seizure threshold matters or in eating disorders.","meds":["bupropion","varenicline","nortriptyline","naltrexone"],"disorder":"Tobacco use disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["tobacco","comorbidity"],"source":{"name":"Bupropion (Zyban) label","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vx_mgmt_agitation_qt_lorazepam","stem":"A 34-year-old is acutely agitated in the emergency department; the chart shows he is maintained on high-dose methadone and the ECG demonstrates a markedly prolonged QTc. He needs rapid parenteral calming. Which is the safest agent?","options":["Lorazepam","Droperidol","Haloperidol","Ziprasidone"],"answer":"Lorazepam","explanation":"Lorazepam is reliably absorbed IM and does not prolong the QT interval, making it the safest choice for rapid tranquillization when the QTc is already prolonged (here compounded by methadone). Droperidol carries a prominent torsades warning even at low doses, IV haloperidol is a recognized torsades risk, and ziprasidone has the greatest QT effect among the SGAs — all are poor choices with a long QTc.","meds":["lorazepam","droperidol","haloperidol","ziprasidone"],"disorder":"Acute agitation","difficulty":2,"tags":["qt","agitation"],"source":{"name":"Droperidol boxed warning / agitation practice","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vx_mgmt_agitation_post_im_olanzapine","stem":"A combative patient has just received IM olanzapine 10 mg for acute agitation but remains agitated 20 minutes later. The nurse asks whether to give IM lorazepam next. What is the most appropriate additional agent?","options":["Haloperidol","Lorazepam","Midazolam","Diazepam"],"answer":"Haloperidol","explanation":"Parenteral benzodiazepines should not be combined with IM olanzapine because of the risk of excessive cardiorespiratory and CNS depression, so lorazepam, midazolam, and diazepam are all unsafe next steps here. Adding haloperidol (with ECG/QT awareness) is the appropriate additional agent when more control is needed after IM olanzapine.","meds":["olanzapine","haloperidol","lorazepam","midazolam","diazepam"],"disorder":"Acute agitation","difficulty":3,"tags":["agitation","interaction"],"source":{"name":"Olanzapine IM label caution","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vx_mgmt_pdpsychosis_first_line_quetiapine","stem":"A 74-year-old with Parkinson disease develops distressing visual hallucinations and paranoid delusions after a dopaminergic dose increase; symptoms persist after the dose is optimized and precipitants are excluded. In Canada, which antipsychotic is the most appropriate first choice?","options":["Quetiapine","Risperidone","Haloperidol","Pimavanserin"],"answer":"Quetiapine","explanation":"Quetiapine binds D2 loosely and has the lowest EPS/prolactin liability, making it the practical go-to in Parkinson disease psychosis because it least worsens parkinsonian motor symptoms. Risperidone (highly D2-potent) and haloperidol (high-potency FGA) both aggravate motor function, and pimavanserin — the mechanistically ideal 5-HT2A inverse agonist with no D2 activity — is not available in Canada.","meds":["quetiapine","risperidone","haloperidol","pimavanserin"],"disorder":"Parkinson disease psychosis","difficulty":2,"tags":["first-line","elderly","eps"],"source":{"name":"PD psychosis management","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vx_mgmt_pdpsychosis_refractory_clozapine","stem":"A 71-year-old with Parkinson disease psychosis remains severely hallucinated and delusional despite an adequate quetiapine trial. Cognition is intact, he consents to regular bloodwork, and pimavanserin is unavailable. Which agent has the best evidence without worsening his motor symptoms?","options":["Clozapine","Olanzapine","Haloperidol","Risperidone"],"answer":"Clozapine","explanation":"Clozapine has the strongest evidence in Parkinson disease psychosis and, with its very loose D2 binding, produces essentially no EPS — appropriate here provided registry ANC monitoring is done. Olanzapine, risperidone, and haloperidol all block D2 more tightly and worsen parkinsonian motor symptoms, so they are inappropriate in this population.","meds":["clozapine","olanzapine","haloperidol","risperidone"],"disorder":"Parkinson disease psychosis","difficulty":3,"tags":["switching","elderly","eps"],"source":{"name":"PD psychosis refractory management","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vx_mgmt_scz_trs_clozapine","stem":"A 28-year-old with schizophrenia has had persistent positive symptoms despite two adequate trials of different antipsychotics at therapeutic doses and duration, with confirmed adherence. What is the most appropriate next-step medication?","options":["Clozapine","Olanzapine","Risperidone","Haloperidol"],"answer":"Clozapine","explanation":"Failure of two adequate antipsychotic trials defines treatment-resistant schizophrenia, for which clozapine is the only antipsychotic proven superior (and the only one shown to reduce suicidality) — it should not be delayed further. Simply switching to another non-clozapine agent such as olanzapine, risperidone, or haloperidol offers no advantage once resistance is established.","meds":["clozapine","olanzapine","risperidone","haloperidol"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":1,"tags":["treatment-resistant","clozapine"],"source":{"name":"Clozapine boxed warning / TRS guidance","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vx_mgmt_scz_lai_aripiprazole","stem":"A 24-year-old man with schizophrenia has relapsed twice from covert non-adherence and now agrees to a long-acting injectable. He is very concerned about weight gain and sexual side effects and has a strong family history of diabetes. Which LAI best fits these priorities?","options":["Aripiprazole","Olanzapine","Paliperidone","Risperidone"],"answer":"Aripiprazole","explanation":"Aripiprazole is a D2 partial agonist that is weight-neutral and prolactin-sparing and is available as a monthly LAI, aligning with his metabolic and sexual-side-effect concerns (watch for akathisia). Olanzapine LAI carries among the worst metabolic risk, while paliperidone and risperidone are the most prolactin-elevating and EPS-prone atypicals, making them poorer fits for his stated priorities.","meds":["aripiprazole","olanzapine","paliperidone","risperidone"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":2,"tags":["lai","adherence","metabolic"],"source":{"name":"Aripiprazole LAI (Maintena) label","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vx_mgmt_bipolar_mania_lithium","stem":"A 30-year-old man presents with a first episode of acute mania. He and his family want a mood stabilizer that is first-line for both acute mania and long-term maintenance and that carries evidence for reducing suicide. Renal and thyroid function are normal. Which agent best fits?","options":["Lithium","Gabapentin","Topiramate","Lamotrigine"],"answer":"Lithium","explanation":"Lithium is CANMAT first-line for acute mania and for maintenance and is the only psychotropic with robust evidence for reducing suicide. Gabapentin and topiramate are not primary mood stabilizers (negative bipolar RCTs), and lamotrigine — while useful for maintenance and bipolar depression — has no role in treating acute mania.","meds":["lithium","gabapentin","topiramate","lamotrigine"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["first-line","canmat","mania"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT/ISBD 2018 Bipolar Guidelines","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_mgmt_bipolar_depression_lurasidone","stem":"A 35-year-old with bipolar I disorder presents in an acute bipolar depressive episode. She is metabolically vulnerable (obese, prediabetic, dyslipidemic) and you want a first-line agent that will not worsen her metabolic profile. Which is the best choice?","options":["Lurasidone","Olanzapine","Quetiapine","Risperidone"],"answer":"Lurasidone","explanation":"Lurasidone is CANMAT first-line for bipolar I depression and is metabolically favourable (weight/lipid/glucose-neutral, low prolactin), making it the best fit for a metabolically vulnerable patient — remember it must be taken with food (≥350 kcal). Olanzapine carries among the worst metabolic risk, quetiapine is first-line but more sedating and metabolically burdensome, and risperidone is not a first-line agent for bipolar depression.","meds":["lurasidone","olanzapine","quetiapine","risperidone"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":3,"tags":["first-line","canmat","metabolic"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT/ISBD 2018 Bipolar Guidelines","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_pop_mdd_pregnancy_ssri","stem":"A 28-year-old woman at 9 weeks' gestation presents with a first episode of major depression severe enough to warrant pharmacotherapy. Which antidepressant is the preferred first choice in pregnancy?","options":["Sertraline","Paroxetine","Fluoxetine","Venlafaxine"],"answer":"Sertraline","explanation":"Sertraline is one of the preferred SSRIs in pregnancy/lactation given its data and low milk transfer (treat maternal illness per CANMAT perinatal). Paroxetine is generally avoided (association with cardiac septal defects); fluoxetine's long half-life and greater milk secretion make it less ideal; venlafaxine risks late-pregnancy neonatal adaptation.","meds":["sertraline","paroxetine","fluoxetine","venlafaxine"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["pregnancy","first-line","canmat"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT perinatal 2024","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_pop_mdd_hepatic_avoid","stem":"A 54-year-old man with major depression has biopsy-proven cirrhosis and ongoing heavy alcohol use. Which antidepressant is best AVOIDED in this patient?","options":["Duloxetine","Sertraline","Escitalopram","Mirtazapine"],"answer":"Duloxetine","explanation":"Duloxetine should be avoided in hepatic impairment and significant alcohol use because of hepatotoxicity. Sertraline, escitalopram, and mirtazapine are all reasonable antidepressant choices here (with escitalopram capped at 10 mg/day if hepatic function is compromised).","meds":["duloxetine","sertraline","escitalopram","mirtazapine"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["hepatic","contraindication"],"source":{"name":"Duloxetine product monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_pop_bipolar_pregnancy_maint","stem":"A 30-year-old woman with bipolar I disorder and predominantly depressive episodes is 6 weeks pregnant and needs maintenance mood stabilization. Which agent is the comparatively safest choice in pregnancy?","options":["Lamotrigine","Valproate / Divalproex","Carbamazepine","Lithium"],"answer":"Lamotrigine","explanation":"Lamotrigine is the comparatively pregnancy-safer, CANMAT-first-line maintenance stabilizer for depression prevention (watch for falling levels antenatally and reduce postpartum). Valproate is the most teratogenic mood stabilizer (neural-tube defects, lowest childhood IQ); carbamazepine also causes neural-tube/craniofacial defects; lithium carries a first-trimester Ebstein-anomaly risk.","meds":["lamotrigine","valproate","carbamazepine","lithium"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["pregnancy","canmat"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT/ISBD 2018 Bipolar; perinatal 2024","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_pop_bipolar_renal_elderly_avoid","stem":"A 74-year-old man with bipolar I disorder is admitted in acute mania. His eGFR is 34 mL/min. Which first-line antimanic agent is best AVOIDED given his age and renal function?","options":["Lithium","Valproate / Divalproex","Quetiapine","Aripiprazole"],"answer":"Lithium","explanation":"Lithium is renally cleared, and reduced clearance in the elderly and in renal impairment narrows its therapeutic window and increases neurotoxicity, so it is best avoided here. Valproate, quetiapine, and aripiprazole are all CANMAT first-line for acute mania and do not depend on renal clearance the way lithium does.","meds":["lithium","valproate","quetiapine","aripiprazole"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["renal","geriatric"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT/ISBD 2018 Bipolar","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_pop_scz_qt_avoid","stem":"A 40-year-old man with schizophrenia has a baseline QTc of 480 ms and takes methadone. Which antipsychotic is best AVOIDED because it carries the greatest QT liability of the second-generation agents?","options":["Ziprasidone","Aripiprazole","Lurasidone","Risperidone"],"answer":"Ziprasidone","explanation":"Ziprasidone causes the greatest QT prolongation of the SGAs and should be avoided alongside other QT-prolonging drugs and with uncorrected electrolytes. Aripiprazole is essentially QT-neutral, lurasidone is low-QT-risk, and risperidone has only a modest QT effect.","meds":["ziprasidone","aripiprazole","lurasidone","risperidone"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":2,"tags":["qt","cardiac"],"source":{"name":"Ziprasidone product label (QT)","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vx_pop_scz_pregnancy_metabolic","stem":"A 27-year-old woman with schizophrenia relapses at 14 weeks' gestation and needs an antipsychotic restarted. She has obesity and impaired fasting glucose. Which agent is least desirable here because of its metabolic burden in pregnancy?","options":["Olanzapine","Aripiprazole","Risperidone","Lurasidone"],"answer":"Olanzapine","explanation":"Olanzapine causes substantial gestational weight gain and glucose dysregulation, an added concern in a patient already at metabolic risk. Aripiprazole, risperidone, and lurasidone lack a clear teratogenic signal and carry a lighter metabolic load, though all three share third-trimester neonatal EPS/withdrawal considerations.","meds":["olanzapine","aripiprazole","risperidone","lurasidone"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":2,"tags":["pregnancy"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT perinatal 2024","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_pop_gad_pregnancy_firstline","stem":"A 31-year-old woman at 11 weeks' gestation has generalized anxiety disorder refractory to psychotherapy and wants medication. Which is the most appropriate first-line pharmacologic choice?","options":["Escitalopram","Paroxetine","Lorazepam","Pregabalin"],"answer":"Escitalopram","explanation":"Escitalopram has no consistent major teratogenic signal and is a reasonable first-line SSRI in pregnancy. Paroxetine is avoided (cardiac malformation signal); regular late-pregnancy lorazepam risks neonatal hypotonia/withdrawal ('floppy infant'); and pregabalin has a possible-harm signal and is avoided if possible.","meds":["escitalopram","paroxetine","lorazepam","pregabalin"],"disorder":"Generalized anxiety disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["pregnancy","first-line"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT perinatal 2024","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_pop_gad_elderly_falls","stem":"A 76-year-old woman with generalized anxiety disorder has had two recent falls. You want an anxiolytic that will not add sedation-related fall risk. Best choice?","options":["Buspirone","Lorazepam","Hydroxyzine","Diazepam"],"answer":"Buspirone","explanation":"Buspirone is approved for GAD and is non-sedating with no sedation-driven fall risk, making it well suited to a frail older adult. Lorazepam and diazepam are Beers-listed benzodiazepines (falls, fractures, delirium), and hydroxyzine is anticholinergic, sedating, and QT-prolonging (also Beers-cautioned).","meds":["buspirone","lorazepam","hydroxyzine","diazepam"],"disorder":"Generalized anxiety disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["geriatric"],"source":{"name":"AGS Beers Criteria (geriatric)","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vx_pop_dementia_pd_psychosis","stem":"A 78-year-old man with Parkinson disease and major neurocognitive disorder develops distressing visual hallucinations. If an antipsychotic is required, which agent best avoids worsening his parkinsonism?","options":["Quetiapine","Haloperidol","Risperidone","Olanzapine"],"answer":"Quetiapine","explanation":"Quetiapine's loose D2 binding gives it the lowest EPS/prolactin of these agents, making it a go-to in Parkinson disease psychosis. Haloperidol is a high-potency FGA with maximal EPS that would markedly worsen motor symptoms; risperidone raises prolactin and EPS; olanzapine adds anticholinergic burden. (All antipsychotics carry a boxed warning for increased mortality in dementia-related psychosis.)","meds":["quetiapine","haloperidol","risperidone","olanzapine"],"disorder":"Major neurocognitive disorder (dementia)","difficulty":2,"tags":["geriatric","eps"],"source":{"name":"Quetiapine product monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_pop_dementia_cardiac_conduction","stem":"An 80-year-old woman with moderate-to-severe Alzheimer dementia has sick sinus syndrome and symptomatic bradycardia. Which cognitive-enhancing agent is safest for her heart?","options":["Memantine","Donepezil","Rivastigmine","Galantamine"],"answer":"Memantine","explanation":"Memantine is an NMDA antagonist with no vagotonic effect, giving it a safer cardiac profile in conduction disease. Donepezil, rivastigmine, and galantamine are all cholinesterase inhibitors whose vagotonic action causes bradycardia and syncope and is cautioned in sick sinus syndrome and other conduction defects.","meds":["memantine","donepezil","rivastigmine","galantamine"],"disorder":"Major neurocognitive disorder (dementia)","difficulty":2,"tags":["cardiac","geriatric"],"source":{"name":"Cholinesterase inhibitor monographs (cardiac)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_pop_delirium_avoid_benzo","stem":"An 82-year-old post-operative man has hyperactive delirium with agitation threatening his surgical drains; non-pharmacologic measures have failed. Which medication is most likely to WORSEN his delirium and should be avoided?","options":["Lorazepam","Haloperidol","Quetiapine","Risperidone"],"answer":"Lorazepam","explanation":"Benzodiazepines such as lorazepam precipitate and prolong delirium in older adults and are Beers-listed for exactly this reason, so they are avoided outside of sedative/alcohol-withdrawal delirium. Low-dose haloperidol, quetiapine, or risperidone are the usual short-term options for a dangerously agitated hyperactive delirium.","meds":["lorazepam","haloperidol","quetiapine","risperidone"],"disorder":"Delirium","difficulty":2,"tags":["delirium","geriatric"],"source":{"name":"AGS Beers Criteria (delirium)","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vx_pop_delirium_etoh_hepatic","stem":"A 66-year-old man with alcoholic cirrhosis is admitted with alcohol-withdrawal delirium (delirium tremens). Which agent is the best first-line choice for symptom-triggered management given his liver disease?","options":["Lorazepam","Diazepam","Chlordiazepoxide","Haloperidol"],"answer":"Lorazepam","explanation":"Lorazepam is a 'LOT' agent cleared by glucuronidation with no active metabolite, making it the benzodiazepine of choice for withdrawal in hepatic impairment and the elderly. Diazepam and chlordiazepoxide have long-acting active metabolites that accumulate in cirrhosis; haloperidol does not treat withdrawal and lowers the seizure threshold.","meds":["lorazepam","diazepam","chlordiazepoxide","haloperidol"],"disorder":"Delirium","difficulty":3,"tags":["hepatic"],"source":{"name":"Lorazepam/diazepam product monographs","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_pop_insomnia_elderly_falls","stem":"A 77-year-old woman with chronic sleep-onset insomnia and a history of falls asks for a sleep aid. Which option best minimizes fall and next-day-sedation risk?","options":["Melatonin","Zopiclone","Zolpidem","Temazepam"],"answer":"Melatonin","explanation":"Endogenous melatonin declines with age, and low-dose melatonin can aid sleep onset with minimal risk, making it the safest listed option for a faller. Zopiclone and zolpidem are Z-drugs (falls, confusion, next-day sedation), and temazepam is a Beers-listed hypnotic benzodiazepine to avoid in older adults.","meds":["melatonin","zopiclone","zolpidem","temazepam"],"disorder":"Insomnia","difficulty":2,"tags":["geriatric"],"source":{"name":"AGS Beers Criteria (hypnotics)","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vx_pop_insomnia_hepatic_lot","stem":"A 70-year-old man with decompensated cirrhosis has severe insomnia and, after non-drug measures fail, a short course of a hypnotic benzodiazepine is chosen. Which agent is preferred in hepatic impairment?","options":["Temazepam","Diazepam","Flurazepam","Nitrazepam"],"answer":"Temazepam","explanation":"Temazepam is a 'LOT' agent (glucuronidation, no active metabolite), so it is liver-safe and preferred when a hypnotic benzodiazepine must be used in hepatic impairment. Diazepam's and flurazepam's long-acting active metabolites accumulate, and nitrazepam's long parent half-life causes next-day impairment.","meds":["temazepam","diazepam","flurazepam","nitrazepam"],"disorder":"Insomnia","difficulty":3,"tags":["hepatic"],"source":{"name":"Temazepam product monograph (LOT agent)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_safe_ss_fluoxetine_washout_1","stem":"A 44-year-old with treatment-resistant depression is being switched to the MAOI phenelzine. Before starting it, which current antidepressant demands a FULL FIVE-WEEK washout (rather than the usual ~14 days) to avoid a fatal serotonin syndrome?","options":["Fluoxetine","Sertraline","Escitalopram","Venlafaxine"],"answer":"Fluoxetine","explanation":"Fluoxetine's long half-life and active metabolite norfluoxetine require a 5-week washout before an MAOI, versus ~14 days for other serotonergics; starting phenelzine too soon risks serotonin syndrome. Sertraline, escitalopram, and venlafaxine clear within roughly two weeks.","meds":["fluoxetine","phenelzine","sertraline","escitalopram","venlafaxine"],"disorder":"Serotonin syndrome","difficulty":2,"tags":["serotonin","interaction"],"source":{"name":"Fluoxetine monograph — MAOI washout","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_safe_ss_manage_cyproheptadine_1","stem":"Two days after tranylcypromine was started with an inadequate washout from venlafaxine, a patient becomes hyperthermic and agitated with spontaneous ocular clonus and brisk hyperreflexia. The team stops all serotonergic agents, actively cools him, gives benzodiazepines, and adds the serotonin antagonist cyproheptadine. Which syndrome are they managing?","options":["Serotonin syndrome","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Anticholinergic toxicity","Lithium toxicity"],"answer":"Serotonin syndrome","explanation":"Rapid-onset clonus and hyperreflexia after two serotonergic agents (an MAOI stacked on venlafaxine without a washout) define serotonin syndrome; management is to STOP serotonergics, cool, sedate with benzodiazepines, and give cyproheptadine. NMS instead evolves over days with rigidity and hyporeflexia, and the others lack clonus.","meds":["tranylcypromine","venlafaxine"],"disorder":"Serotonin syndrome","difficulty":2,"tags":["serotonin","interaction"],"source":{"name":"FRCPC serotonin syndrome management (Hunter criteria)","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vx_safe_nms_stop_antipsychotic_1","stem":"Five days after starting haloperidol, a patient is febrile (40°C) with generalised lead-pipe rigidity, hyporeflexia, fluctuating consciousness, labile blood pressure, and CK 8000. Beyond aggressive cooling and IV fluids, what is the single most important FIRST management step, defining the syndrome you are treating?","options":["Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Serotonin syndrome","Anticholinergic toxicity","Hypertensive crisis (tyramine reaction)"],"answer":"Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","explanation":"NMS mandates immediate discontinuation of the dopamine antagonist plus supportive care (cooling, fluids), with dantrolene and a dopamine agonist for severe cases. Serotonin syndrome would show clonus/hyperreflexia and respond to cyproheptadine; anticholinergic toxicity lacks rigidity and CK rise; a tyramine reaction is a pure pressor crisis without rigidity.","meds":["haloperidol"],"disorder":"Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","difficulty":2,"tags":["nms"],"source":{"name":"FRCPC NMS management","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vx_safe_nms_dopaminergic_agent_1","stem":"A patient with severe neuroleptic malignant syndrome has had the antipsychotic stopped and dantrolene started. The team wants to add a dopaminergic agent to counter the dopamine blockade. Which formulary agent is a dopaminergic/NMDA-antagonist used for this purpose (and also for drug-induced parkinsonism)?","options":["Amantadine","Benztropine","Propranolol","Lorazepam"],"answer":"Amantadine","explanation":"Amantadine is a dopaminergic + NMDA antagonist used adjunctively in NMS to reverse dopamine blockade (bromocriptine is the classic dopamine agonist, amantadine an alternative) — and it must not be stopped abruptly, which itself can trigger an NMS-like withdrawal. Benztropine (anticholinergic) treats dystonia/parkinsonism, propranolol treats akathisia, and lorazepam targets agitation/catatonia, not the dopamine deficit.","meds":["amantadine","benztropine","propranolol","lorazepam"],"disorder":"Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","difficulty":3,"tags":["nms"],"source":{"name":"Amantadine monograph — dopaminergic/NMDA","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_safe_lithium_avoid_renal_1","stem":"A 72-year-old with bipolar I, stage 3 CKD (eGFR 34), and regular NSAID use for arthritis needs maintenance mood stabilization. Which agent is best AVOIDED here because reduced renal clearance readily precipitates toxicity?","options":["Lithium","Valproate","Lamotrigine","Quetiapine"],"answer":"Lithium","explanation":"Lithium is renally excreted and not metabolized, so CKD, NSAIDs, thiazides, ACEi/ARBs, and dehydration cut its clearance and precipitate toxicity — avoid or use with great caution in renal impairment. Valproate, lamotrigine, and quetiapine are cleared hepatically and spare the kidney (each with its own separate cautions).","meds":["lithium","valproate","lamotrigine","quetiapine"],"disorder":"Lithium toxicity","difficulty":2,"tags":["monitoring","elderly"],"source":{"name":"Lithium monograph — renal clearance/DDI","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_safe_lithium_toxicity_dialysis_1","stem":"A patient on chronic lithium presents with a coarse tremor, ataxia, and confusion; the level is 3.2 mmol/L with acute kidney injury. Management is to hold lithium, give IV normal saline, and arrange hemodialysis. Which toxic syndrome, at which the dialysis threshold has been crossed, does this describe?","options":["Lithium toxicity","Serotonin syndrome","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Anticholinergic toxicity"],"answer":"Lithium toxicity","explanation":"Coarse tremor, ataxia, and confusion with a level >2.5 mmol/L plus renal failure is severe lithium toxicity — hold lithium, restore volume with saline, and dialyze (indicated at >4, or >2.5 with symptoms/renal failure). The clonus of serotonin syndrome and the rigidity/CK rise of NMS are absent.","meds":["lithium"],"disorder":"Lithium toxicity","difficulty":2,"tags":["overdose","monitoring"],"source":{"name":"Lithium monograph — toxicity/dialysis","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_safe_anticholinergic_tca_bicarb_1","stem":"A teenager brought in after an amitriptyline overdose is delirious, dry, and flushed with dilated pupils and a QRS of 130 ms. The team gives IV sodium bicarbonate for the widened QRS and specifically AVOIDS physostigmine. Which toxidrome underlies the peripheral findings, and what governs this management?","options":["Anticholinergic toxicity","Serotonin syndrome","Lithium toxicity","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome"],"answer":"Anticholinergic toxicity","explanation":"TCA overdose pairs an anticholinergic toxidrome (dry/flushed skin, mydriasis, ileus, delirium) with life-threatening sodium-channel-blockade cardiotoxicity — treat QRS >100 ms with sodium bicarbonate; physostigmine is avoided in TCA poisoning because it can precipitate asystole and seizures. There is no clonus (serotonin syndrome) or rigidity (NMS).","meds":["amitriptyline"],"disorder":"Anticholinergic toxicity","difficulty":2,"tags":["overdose"],"source":{"name":"Amitriptyline monograph — overdose management","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_safe_anticholinergic_avoid_elderly_1","stem":"An 80-year-old with dementia, chronic constipation, BPH with urinary hesitancy, and narrow-angle glaucoma needs an antidepressant. Which is the WORST choice because its high anticholinergic burden risks delirium, urinary retention, ileus, and acute angle-closure?","options":["Amitriptyline","Sertraline","Escitalopram","Mirtazapine"],"answer":"Amitriptyline","explanation":"Amitriptyline is a strongly anticholinergic tertiary-amine TCA — in a frail elderly patient with BPH, constipation, and narrow-angle glaucoma it risks delirium, urinary retention, paralytic ileus, and acute angle-closure. Sertraline and escitalopram are minimally anticholinergic, and mirtazapine is chiefly antihistaminergic rather than anticholinergic.","meds":["amitriptyline","sertraline","escitalopram","mirtazapine"],"disorder":"Anticholinergic toxicity","difficulty":2,"tags":["elderly","overdose"],"source":{"name":"Amitriptyline monograph — anticholinergic burden","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_safe_tyramine_avoid_sympathomimetic_1","stem":"A patient stable on phenelzine for treatment-resistant depression asks about a medication for newly diagnosed ADHD. Which agent is CONTRAINDICATED because, potentiated by MAO inhibition, it can precipitate a hypertensive crisis?","options":["Dextroamphetamine","Guanfacine","Clonidine","Propranolol"],"answer":"Dextroamphetamine","explanation":"MAOIs potentiate sympathomimetics — amphetamines, methylphenidate, and other indirect pressors are explicitly contraindicated with phenelzine and can trigger the same hypertensive crisis seen with tyramine. The three distractors LOWER blood pressure: guanfacine and clonidine are central alpha-2 agonists and propranolol is a beta-blocker.","meds":["phenelzine","dextroamphetamine","guanfacine","clonidine","propranolol"],"disorder":"Hypertensive crisis (tyramine reaction)","difficulty":2,"tags":["interaction"],"source":{"name":"Phenelzine monograph — contraindicated sympathomimetics","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_safe_eps_acute_dystonia_1","stem":"Hours after a first IM dose of haloperidol, a young man develops a sustained painful upward deviation of the eyes with neck twisting (oculogyric crisis / acute dystonia). What is the correct immediate treatment?","options":["Benztropine","Propranolol","Valbenazine","Lithium"],"answer":"Benztropine","explanation":"Acute dystonia is a medical urgency treated with a parenteral anticholinergic — IM/IV benztropine (or procyclidine/diphenhydramine) rapidly rebalances striatal ACh vs dopamine. Propranolol is for akathisia, VMAT2 inhibitors like valbenazine are for tardive dyskinesia, and lithium is irrelevant.","meds":["benztropine","haloperidol","propranolol","valbenazine"],"disorder":"Extrapyramidal symptoms","difficulty":1,"tags":["eps"],"source":{"name":"Benztropine monograph — acute dystonia","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_safe_eps_akathisia_propranolol_1","stem":"A patient started on aripiprazole cannot sit still, paces constantly, and reports a distressing inner restlessness (akathisia). After considering an antipsychotic dose reduction, which agent is FIRST-LINE pharmacologic treatment?","options":["Propranolol","Benztropine","Trihexyphenidyl","Amantadine"],"answer":"Propranolol","explanation":"Propranolol (a lipophilic beta-blocker) is first-line for antipsychotic-induced akathisia, alongside lowering the dose or a short benzodiazepine course; anticholinergics (benztropine, trihexyphenidyl) do NOT reliably relieve akathisia, and amantadine is for parkinsonism. Aripiprazole is notably activating with prominent akathisia.","meds":["propranolol","aripiprazole","benztropine","trihexyphenidyl","amantadine"],"disorder":"Extrapyramidal symptoms","difficulty":2,"tags":["eps"],"source":{"name":"Propranolol monograph — akathisia","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_safe_eps_parkinsonism_amantadine_1","stem":"A 78-year-old on risperidone develops drug-induced parkinsonism (bradykinesia, cogwheel rigidity, resting tremor). You want to treat the EPS while MINIMIZING anticholinergic burden because of her cognitive impairment. Which agent is preferred?","options":["Amantadine","Benztropine","Trihexyphenidyl","Procyclidine"],"answer":"Amantadine","explanation":"Amantadine (dopaminergic/NMDA antagonist) treats drug-induced parkinsonism with far LESS anticholinergic burden than benztropine, trihexyphenidyl, or procyclidine — important in the elderly, where anticholinergics cause delirium and falls. Reduce its dose in renal impairment and taper rather than stop abruptly; lowering the antipsychotic dose or switching to a lower-EPS agent also helps.","meds":["amantadine","risperidone","benztropine","trihexyphenidyl","procyclidine"],"disorder":"Extrapyramidal symptoms","difficulty":2,"tags":["eps","elderly"],"source":{"name":"Amantadine monograph — drug-induced parkinsonism","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_safe_td_stop_anticholinergic_1","stem":"A patient on a long-term antipsychotic develops choreoathetoid tongue and lip movements (tardive dyskinesia). She is also taking benztropine for earlier parkinsonism. Which of her medications should be STOPPED because it can WORSEN tardive dyskinesia?","options":["Benztropine","Propranolol","Amantadine","Quetiapine"],"answer":"Benztropine","explanation":"Anticholinergics such as benztropine WORSEN tardive dyskinesia (they help parkinsonism but unmask dopamine-receptor hypersensitivity) and should be discontinued when TD emerges. Amantadine may actually improve TD, propranolol targets akathisia, and switching toward a lower-D2 agent like quetiapine or clozapine is a reasonable additional step.","meds":["benztropine","propranolol","amantadine","quetiapine"],"disorder":"Tardive dyskinesia","difficulty":3,"tags":["td","eps"],"source":{"name":"Benztropine monograph — worsens tardive dyskinesia","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_safe_td_vmat2_inhibitor_1","stem":"A patient has persistent, disabling tardive dyskinesia despite stopping anticholinergics and reviewing the antipsychotic. Which agent is an evidence-based, VMAT2-inhibitor treatment specifically for tardive dyskinesia?","options":["Deutetrabenazine","Benztropine","Propranolol","Donepezil"],"answer":"Deutetrabenazine","explanation":"VMAT2 inhibitors (deutetrabenazine, valbenazine, tetrabenazine) deplete presynaptic dopamine and are the evidence-based treatment for tardive dyskinesia — monitor for parkinsonism, QT prolongation, and depression/suicidality. Benztropine actually worsens TD, propranolol treats akathisia, and donepezil (a cholinesterase inhibitor) is unrelated.","meds":["deutetrabenazine","benztropine","propranolol","donepezil"],"disorder":"Tardive dyskinesia","difficulty":2,"tags":["td","qt"],"source":{"name":"Deutetrabenazine monograph — VMAT2 for TD","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vx_seq_mdd_residual_cognition","stem":"A 41-year-old software developer with major depression has taken sertraline at an adequate dose for 8 weeks. Her mood and sleep have improved, but she remains distressed by persistent difficulty concentrating and slowed processing that impair her work, and she strongly wishes to avoid worsening the sexual side effects she already has. Which switch best targets her residual symptoms?","options":["Vortioxetine","Amitriptyline","Paroxetine","Phenelzine"],"answer":"Vortioxetine","explanation":"For a partial responder whose residual burden is cognitive dysfunction with a wish to limit sexual side effects, vortioxetine (multimodal, marketed for cognitive symptoms of depression, lower sexual dysfunction than SSRIs) is the best-matched switch. Amitriptyline and paroxetine are anticholinergic and worsen cognition/sexual function, and phenelzine is a later-line MAOI reserved for treatment resistance.","meds":["vortioxetine","amitriptyline","paroxetine","phenelzine"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["switching","residual-symptoms","canmat"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT 2016 MDD Guidelines","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_seq_mdd_augment_suicide","stem":"A 55-year-old with recurrent major depression has failed two adequate antidepressant trials and now has only a partial response to venlafaxine, which he tolerates well. He has chronic passive suicidal ideation and a prior attempt. You elect to augment rather than switch. Which agent adds the strongest evidence for reducing suicide risk in this setting?","options":["Lithium","Gabapentin","Buspirone","Trazodone"],"answer":"Lithium","explanation":"Lithium augmentation of an antidepressant is an established treatment-resistant-depression strategy and is the only psychotropic with robust evidence for reducing suicide, making it the best choice given his chronic suicidality. Gabapentin has no antidepressant evidence, and buspirone or trazodone augmentation may help symptoms but carry no anti-suicide benefit.","meds":["lithium","gabapentin","buspirone","trazodone"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":3,"tags":["augmentation","treatment-resistant","suicide"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT 2016 MDD Guidelines","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_seq_gad_augment_no_dependence","stem":"A 34-year-old with generalized anxiety disorder and a history of alcohol use disorder in sustained remission has a partial response to escitalopram after 10 weeks. He and you agree to add a daily anxiolytic while explicitly avoiding any agent with dependence potential. Which is the best add-on?","options":["Buspirone","Clonazepam","Diazepam","Alprazolam"],"answer":"Buspirone","explanation":"Buspirone is approved for GAD, augments antidepressants, and has no dependence or abuse potential, making it the anxiolytic of choice when a substance-use history rules out benzodiazepines. Clonazepam, diazepam, and alprazolam all carry tolerance and dependence risk that is inappropriate here.","meds":["buspirone","clonazepam","diazepam","alprazolam"],"disorder":"Generalized anxiety disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["augmentation","substance-use","canmat"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_seq_gad_switch_comorbid_pain","stem":"A 62-year-old with generalized anxiety disorder has had no meaningful response to escitalopram at maximum tolerated dose over 12 weeks. She also has fibromyalgia and chronic musculoskeletal pain that dominate her presentation. Which switch best covers both her anxiety and her pain?","options":["Duloxetine","Bupropion","Desvenlafaxine","Mirtazapine"],"answer":"Duloxetine","explanation":"Duloxetine is approved for GAD and for fibromyalgia and chronic musculoskeletal pain, so a single switch addresses both problems. Bupropion lacks anxiety efficacy, desvenlafaxine is approved only for depression (GAD is off-label with no pain indication), and mirtazapine covers neither GAD nor pain.","meds":["duloxetine","bupropion","desvenlafaxine","mirtazapine"],"disorder":"Generalized anxiety disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["switching","comorbidity","canmat"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_seq_ocd_switch_clomipramine","stem":"A 28-year-old with obsessive-compulsive disorder has been pushed to a high dose of sertraline for 12 weeks and separately failed an adequate high-dose fluoxetine trial, with minimal reduction in obsessions. You want to switch to the agent with the strongest disorder-specific antiobsessional evidence. Which do you choose?","options":["Clomipramine","Amitriptyline","Bupropion","Venlafaxine"],"answer":"Clomipramine","explanation":"After adequate high-dose, long-duration SSRI trials fail in OCD, clomipramine is the evidence-based next step as the most serotonergic TCA and the only tricyclic with robust antiobsessional efficacy. Amitriptyline and bupropion have no OCD efficacy, and venlafaxine has only weak OCD evidence.","meds":["clomipramine","amitriptyline","bupropion","venlafaxine"],"disorder":"Obsessive-compulsive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["switching","high-dose","canmat"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_seq_ocd_augment_antipsychotic","stem":"A 37-year-old with obsessive-compulsive disorder and comorbid chronic motor tics has had adequate trials of two high-dose SSRIs and clomipramine, achieving only a partial response. The next-step strategy is low-dose antipsychotic augmentation. Which agent has the best evidence for augmenting an SSRI in treatment-resistant OCD?","options":["Risperidone","Lithium","Lamotrigine","Buspirone"],"answer":"Risperidone","explanation":"Adding a low-dose antipsychotic such as risperidone to an SSRI is the evidence-based augmentation for treatment-resistant OCD, and its benefit is greatest with comorbid tics. Lithium augmentation is a depression strategy, lamotrigine has no OCD evidence, and buspirone augmentation is ineffective for OCD.","meds":["risperidone","lithium","lamotrigine","buspirone"],"disorder":"Obsessive-compulsive disorder","difficulty":3,"tags":["augmentation","treatment-resistant","canmat"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_seq_ptsd_adjunct_nightmares","stem":"A 44-year-old veteran with PTSD has improved overall on sertraline after 10 weeks, with reduced avoidance and hyperarousal, but continues to have distressing recurrent trauma-related nightmares that fragment his sleep. What is the best targeted add-on?","options":["Prazosin","Quetiapine","Zopiclone","Clonazepam"],"answer":"Prazosin","explanation":"Prazosin at bedtime is the evidence-based adjunct for PTSD-associated nightmares and trauma-related sleep disruption, directly targeting his residual symptom. Quetiapine carries an unfavourable metabolic/sedation burden for this indication, zopiclone treats insomnia but not nightmares, and benzodiazepines such as clonazepam are discouraged in PTSD and do not address nightmares.","meds":["prazosin","quetiapine","zopiclone","clonazepam"],"disorder":"Post-traumatic stress disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["augmentation","residual-symptoms"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_seq_ptsd_switch_snri","stem":"A 39-year-old with PTSD has had an adequate 12-week trial of paroxetine with inadequate response and is bothered by weight gain and difficult discontinuation symptoms on missed doses. You decide to switch to another agent with randomized-trial evidence in PTSD. Which is the best choice?","options":["Venlafaxine","Bupropion","Trazodone","Amitriptyline"],"answer":"Venlafaxine","explanation":"Venlafaxine (SNRI) has randomized controlled evidence in PTSD and is an appropriate first-line-equivalent switch after an SSRI fails. Bupropion has no PTSD efficacy, trazodone is used mainly for sleep rather than core PTSD symptoms, and amitriptyline is a later-line, poorly tolerated tricyclic.","meds":["venlafaxine","bupropion","trazodone","amitriptyline"],"disorder":"Post-traumatic stress disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["switching","canmat"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_seq_sad_switch_rima","stem":"A 30-year-old with generalized social anxiety disorder has failed adequate trials of two SSRIs and venlafaxine. You are choosing the next-step agent and want an antidepressant with a Canadian social anxiety indication that avoids the dietary tyramine restriction of an irreversible MAOI. Which do you select?","options":["Moclobemide","Phenelzine","Bupropion","Desvenlafaxine"],"answer":"Moclobemide","explanation":"Moclobemide, a reversible inhibitor of MAO-A, is approved for social anxiety disorder and is preferred before an irreversible MAOI because it does not require strict tyramine dietary restriction. Phenelzine works for social anxiety but is a later-line irreversible MAOI needing dietary precautions, bupropion is ineffective for social anxiety, and desvenlafaxine has no anxiety indication.","meds":["moclobemide","phenelzine","bupropion","desvenlafaxine"],"disorder":"Social anxiety disorder","difficulty":3,"tags":["switching","treatment-resistant","canmat"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_seq_sad_performance_prn","stem":"A 26-year-old violinist reports intense anxiety with palpitations and tremor confined to solo public performances a few times a month; she is asymptomatic in all other social situations. She wants something to use only for those events. What is the best next step?","options":["Propranolol","Sertraline","Clonazepam","Buspirone"],"answer":"Propranolol","explanation":"For discrete performance (non-generalized) social anxiety, a PRN beta-blocker such as propranolol before the event blunts the autonomic symptoms (palpitations, tremor) and is the preferred targeted strategy. A daily SSRI like sertraline is disproportionate for isolated performance anxiety, PRN clonazepam carries dependence risk, and buspirone is ineffective taken PRN.","meds":["propranolol","sertraline","clonazepam","buspirone"],"disorder":"Social anxiety disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["first-line","prn"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_seq_panic_bridge_benzo","stem":"A 33-year-old with panic disorder is starting low-dose sertraline. In the first two weeks she has frequent, disabling panic attacks and cannot work while waiting for the SSRI to take effect. You add a time-limited scheduled agent to bridge the latency. Which is the most appropriate?","options":["Clonazepam","Buspirone","Propranolol","Zopiclone"],"answer":"Clonazepam","explanation":"Clonazepam is approved for panic disorder and, given its long half-life and consequent smooth coverage, is a suitable short-term scheduled bridge while the SSRI reaches efficacy. Buspirone is ineffective for panic, propranolol does not prevent panic attacks, and zopiclone is a hypnotic with no antipanic action.","meds":["clonazepam","buspirone","propranolol","zopiclone"],"disorder":"Panic disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["cross-taper","bridging"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_seq_panic_switch_snri","stem":"A 47-year-old with panic disorder has had an adequate 12-week trial of paroxetine with persistent frequent attacks and troublesome weight gain. You plan to switch to another agent with an approved panic disorder indication. Which is the best choice?","options":["Venlafaxine","Bupropion","Mirtazapine","Desvenlafaxine"],"answer":"Venlafaxine","explanation":"Venlafaxine is approved for panic disorder and is an appropriate evidence-based switch after an SSRI fails. Bupropion can worsen anxiety and is not effective for panic, while mirtazapine and desvenlafaxine lack a panic disorder indication.","meds":["venlafaxine","bupropion","mirtazapine","desvenlafaxine"],"disorder":"Panic disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["switching","canmat"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_seq_bpii_depression_firstline","stem":"A 29-year-old with bipolar II disorder presents in an acute depressive episode. A walk-in physician had recently started citalopram monotherapy, without a mood stabilizer. You reassess and choose an evidence-based first-line treatment for the acute bipolar depression. Which is best?","options":["Quetiapine","Bupropion","Desvenlafaxine","Gabapentin"],"answer":"Quetiapine","explanation":"Quetiapine is CANMAT first-line for acute bipolar depression and appropriately replaces antidepressant monotherapy, which is discouraged in bipolar disorder because of limited efficacy and switch risk. Bupropion and desvenlafaxine are antidepressants that should not be used as monotherapy here, and gabapentin has no efficacy in bipolar depression.","meds":["quetiapine","bupropion","desvenlafaxine","gabapentin"],"disorder":"Bipolar II disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["first-line","canmat"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT/ISBD 2018 Bipolar Guidelines","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vx_seq_bpii_maintenance_polarity","stem":"A 45-year-old with bipolar II disorder is now euthymic after an acute episode. Reviewing her course, her recurrences are overwhelmingly depressive, with no history of significant hypomanic relapse, and you are selecting a maintenance agent to best prevent further depressive episodes. Which is the best choice?","options":["Lamotrigine","Valproate / Divalproex","Risperidone","Aripiprazole"],"answer":"Lamotrigine","explanation":"Lamotrigine is CANMAT first-line for bipolar maintenance with a depression-prevention profile, making it ideal for a predominantly depressive course. Valproate, risperidone, and aripiprazole are anti-manic agents that do not provide the same protection against depressive recurrence.","meds":["lamotrigine","valproate","risperidone","aripiprazole"],"disorder":"Bipolar II disorder","difficulty":3,"tags":["maintenance","residual-symptoms","canmat"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT/ISBD 2018 Bipolar Guidelines","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_mdd_cardiac_post_mi_1","stem":"A 64-year-old man develops a major depressive episode 6 weeks after an acute myocardial infarction. He needs an antidepressant with the best cardiac safety evidence in this population. Which is the best choice?","options":["Sertraline","Amitriptyline","Citalopram","Venlafaxine"],"answer":"Sertraline","explanation":"Sertraline is the preferred antidepressant post-MI (SADHART evidence) with a clean cardiac profile. Amitriptyline (TCA) is cardiotoxic and slows conduction, citalopram carries dose-dependent QT prolongation, and venlafaxine raises blood pressure at higher doses.","meds":["sertraline","amitriptyline","citalopram","venlafaxine"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["special-population","cardiac","qt","canmat"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT 2016 MDD; SADHART","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_mdd_bulimia_contra_1","stem":"A 24-year-old woman with major depression and active bulimia nervosa needs an antidepressant. Which agent is CONTRAINDICATED?","options":["Bupropion","Fluoxetine","Sertraline","Escitalopram"],"answer":"Bupropion","explanation":"Bupropion lowers the seizure threshold and is contraindicated in eating disorders (bulimia/anorexia) and seizure disorders due to elevated seizure risk. SSRIs are safe here — fluoxetine is in fact the antidepressant of choice for bulimia.","meds":["bupropion","fluoxetine","sertraline","escitalopram"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["contraindication","seizure","eating-disorder"],"source":{"name":"Bupropion product monograph (deck)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"va_mdd_elderly_mirtazapine_1","stem":"An 80-year-old woman with major depression has prominent insomnia, poor appetite, and 6 kg of weight loss. Which antidepressant best targets her presentation?","options":["Mirtazapine","Bupropion","Fluoxetine","Venlafaxine"],"answer":"Mirtazapine","explanation":"Mirtazapine's H1 antihistamine effect promotes sleep and appetite/weight gain, making it ideal for depressed elderly patients with insomnia and cachexia; 5-HT3 blockade also limits nausea. Bupropion and fluoxetine are activating (worsen insomnia and anorexia), and venlafaxine is not appetite-promoting.","meds":["mirtazapine","bupropion","fluoxetine","venlafaxine"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["special-population","elderly"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT 2016 MDD; mirtazapine monograph (deck)","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_mdd_trd_lithium_augment_1","stem":"A 45-year-old with unipolar major depression has not responded to two adequate SSRI/SNRI trials. You want to add an evidence-based augmenting agent that also lowers suicide risk. Best choice?","options":["Lithium","Gabapentin","Buspirone","Diazepam"],"answer":"Lithium","explanation":"Lithium is a classic evidence-based augmentation strategy in treatment-resistant unipolar depression and is the only psychotropic with robust anti-suicide evidence. Gabapentin and benzodiazepines lack antidepressant efficacy; buspirone augmentation is weaker and unrelated to suicide reduction.","meds":["lithium","gabapentin","buspirone","diazepam"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["treatment-resistant","augmentation","canmat"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT 2016 MDD; lithium data (deck)","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_mdd_trd_esketamine_1","stem":"A 38-year-old with treatment-resistant depression and acute suicidal ideation needs a rapidly acting option delivered in-clinic under monitoring, paired with an oral antidepressant. Which agent fits?","options":["Esketamine","Sertraline","Amitriptyline","Moclobemide"],"answer":"Esketamine","explanation":"Intranasal esketamine acts within hours and is indicated for treatment-resistant depression and MDD with acute suicidality; it is given in-clinic under a REMS-type program with ≥2 h monitoring and always combined with an oral antidepressant. The oral agents take 2–6 weeks to work.","meds":["esketamine","sertraline","amitriptyline","moclobemide"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["treatment-resistant","monitoring"],"source":{"name":"Esketamine monograph (deck)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"va_mdd_atypical_maoi_1","stem":"A 34-year-old with recurrent atypical depression — mood reactivity, hypersomnia, hyperphagia, leaden paralysis, and rejection sensitivity — has failed sequential SSRI and SNRI trials. Which agent has the strongest historical evidence for this subtype?","options":["Phenelzine","Bupropion","Nortriptyline","Lithium"],"answer":"Phenelzine","explanation":"Irreversible MAOIs, classically phenelzine, are the historical agents of choice for refractory atypical depression. Before starting, allow the required washout from serotonergic drugs (e.g., 5 weeks after fluoxetine) and counsel on the tyramine diet. TCAs are less effective in atypical depression than MAOIs.","meds":["phenelzine","bupropion","nortriptyline","lithium"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":3,"tags":["treatment-resistant","washout","serotonin"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT 2016 MDD; phenelzine monograph (deck)","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_gad_first_line_1","stem":"A 29-year-old with newly diagnosed generalized anxiety disorder and no substance-use history wants first-line pharmacotherapy. Best initial choice?","options":["Escitalopram","Alprazolam","Buspirone","Quetiapine"],"answer":"Escitalopram","explanation":"An SSRI (escitalopram) is first-line for GAD — effective, well tolerated, and non-dependence-forming. Benzodiazepines like alprazolam risk tolerance/dependence and are not first-line maintenance; buspirone is a second-line/augmenting option; quetiapine is off-label with a heavy side-effect burden.","meds":["escitalopram","alprazolam","buspirone","quetiapine"],"disorder":"Generalized anxiety disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line","canmat"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_gad_sud_buspirone_1","stem":"A 41-year-old with generalized anxiety disorder and active alcohol use disorder needs an anxiolytic with no abuse or dependence potential. Which is most appropriate?","options":["Buspirone","Diazepam","Lorazepam","Alprazolam"],"answer":"Buspirone","explanation":"Buspirone (5-HT1A partial agonist) has no dependence or abuse potential and is a preferred anxiolytic in patients with a substance-use history; it must be taken daily and takes ~2 weeks to work. The benzodiazepines all carry dependence risk and are hazardous in active alcohol use disorder.","meds":["buspirone","diazepam","lorazepam","alprazolam"],"disorder":"Generalized anxiety disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["special-population","substance-use"],"source":{"name":"Buspirone monograph (deck)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"va_panic_first_line_1","stem":"A 31-year-old with panic disorder wants maintenance pharmacotherapy. Which is the best first-line long-term agent (started low and titrated slowly)?","options":["Sertraline","Alprazolam","Bupropion","Propranolol"],"answer":"Sertraline","explanation":"SSRIs such as sertraline are first-line for panic disorder; start low and go slow because initial activation can transiently worsen panic. Alprazolam works acutely but risks dependence and is not preferred for maintenance; bupropion is activating and not indicated; propranolol does not treat panic disorder.","meds":["sertraline","alprazolam","bupropion","propranolol"],"disorder":"Panic disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line","canmat"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_ocd_first_line_1","stem":"A 27-year-old with obsessive-compulsive disorder is starting pharmacotherapy. Which is an appropriate first-line agent, recognizing OCD often needs higher doses and a longer trial?","options":["Fluvoxamine","Bupropion","Nortriptyline","Lithium"],"answer":"Fluvoxamine","explanation":"SSRIs are first-line for OCD, often at higher doses and with a 10–12 week trial; fluvoxamine is a go-to agent. Bupropion (NDRI) and nortriptyline (a noradrenergic TCA) lack anti-obsessional efficacy, and lithium is not a primary OCD treatment.","meds":["fluvoxamine","bupropion","nortriptyline","lithium"],"disorder":"Obsessive-compulsive disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line","canmat"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_ocd_clomipramine_1","stem":"A 33-year-old with severe OCD has failed adequate trials of three different SSRIs. Which agent has the strongest evidence as the next step?","options":["Clomipramine","Amitriptyline","Desipramine","Imipramine"],"answer":"Clomipramine","explanation":"Clomipramine, the most serotonergic TCA, is the historical gold-standard for OCD and the only TCA with robust anti-obsessional efficacy — the classic choice after SSRI failure. The other TCAs are more noradrenergic and ineffective for OCD; watch clomipramine's dose-dependent seizure risk (250 mg/day ceiling).","meds":["clomipramine","amitriptyline","desipramine","imipramine"],"disorder":"Obsessive-compulsive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["treatment-resistant","seizure"],"source":{"name":"Clomipramine monograph (deck)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"va_ptsd_first_line_1","stem":"A 36-year-old veteran with PTSD is starting pharmacotherapy alongside trauma-focused psychotherapy. Which is an appropriate first-line medication?","options":["Sertraline","Alprazolam","Bupropion","Lithium"],"answer":"Sertraline","explanation":"SSRIs (sertraline, paroxetine) are first-line for PTSD. Benzodiazepines such as alprazolam are specifically discouraged — they do not treat core PTSD symptoms, may impair fear extinction, and carry dependence risk in a high-comorbidity population. Bupropion and lithium are not PTSD treatments.","meds":["sertraline","alprazolam","bupropion","lithium"],"disorder":"Post-traumatic stress disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line","canmat"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_ptsd_prazosin_1","stem":"A 44-year-old with PTSD is stable on an SSRI but has disabling recurrent trauma nightmares and fragmented sleep. Which adjunct specifically targets this symptom?","options":["Prazosin","Zopiclone","Quetiapine","Clonazepam"],"answer":"Prazosin","explanation":"Prazosin, an α1-antagonist dosed at bedtime, is the off-label go-to for PTSD-associated nightmares and trauma-related sleep disruption. Warn about the first-dose orthostatic hypotension/syncope and start at 1 mg. Z-drugs, quetiapine, and benzodiazepines do not selectively address trauma nightmares.","meds":["prazosin","zopiclone","quetiapine","clonazepam"],"disorder":"Post-traumatic stress disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["special-population","adjunct"],"source":{"name":"Prazosin monograph (deck)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"va_social_generalized_first_line_1","stem":"A 25-year-old with generalized social anxiety disorder (pervasive fear across most social situations) wants ongoing pharmacotherapy. Best first-line choice?","options":["Paroxetine","Propranolol","Buspirone","Amitriptyline"],"answer":"Paroxetine","explanation":"SSRIs/SNRIs (e.g., paroxetine) are first-line for generalized social anxiety disorder. Propranolol helps only discrete performance (situational) anxiety, not the generalized subtype; buspirone is not established for SAD; and amitriptyline (TCA) is not a first-line anxiety agent.","meds":["paroxetine","propranolol","buspirone","amitriptyline"],"disorder":"Social anxiety disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line","canmat"],"source":{"name":"Canadian Anxiety Guidelines 2014","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_social_performance_propranolol_1","stem":"A 30-year-old violinist has isolated performance anxiety — palpitations, tremor, and sweating only when playing on stage — and wants an as-needed agent for the physical symptoms. Which is most appropriate?","options":["Propranolol","Sertraline","Buspirone","Clonazepam"],"answer":"Propranolol","explanation":"For discrete performance (situational) social anxiety, a PRN beta-blocker such as propranolol blunts the autonomic symptoms (tremor, palpitations) without sedation or dependence. SSRIs are for generalized SAD and take weeks; a benzodiazepine risks dependence and impairs fine motor performance.","meds":["propranolol","sertraline","buspirone","clonazepam"],"disorder":"Social anxiety disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["performance","adjunct"],"source":{"name":"Propranolol monograph (deck)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"va_bipolar_mania_lithium_1","stem":"A 26-year-old man with bipolar I disorder presents with a first euphoric manic episode and a strong family history of good lithium response. You want a first-line monotherapy that also reduces long-term suicide risk. Best choice?","options":["Lithium","Lamotrigine","Bupropion","Sertraline"],"answer":"Lithium","explanation":"Lithium is CANMAT/ISBD first-line for acute mania and maintenance and uniquely reduces suicide risk, with a good family-history predictor of response. Lamotrigine is ineffective for acute mania, and antidepressants (bupropion, sertraline) can precipitate or worsen mania.","meds":["lithium","lamotrigine","bupropion","sertraline"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line","mania","canmat"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT/ISBD 2018 Bipolar Guidelines","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_bipolar_depression_lurasidone_1","stem":"A 40-year-old with bipolar I disorder presents in an acute bipolar depressive episode and you want first-line monotherapy with a favourable metabolic profile. Which is an appropriate choice?","options":["Lurasidone","Fluoxetine","Diazepam","Carbamazepine"],"answer":"Lurasidone","explanation":"Lurasidone is CANMAT/ISBD first-line for acute bipolar depression and is relatively metabolically favourable. Antidepressant monotherapy (fluoxetine) is avoided in bipolar depression (mood-switch/cycling risk), a benzodiazepine does not treat the depression, and carbamazepine is not a first-line agent for the depressive pole.","meds":["lurasidone","fluoxetine","diazepam","carbamazepine"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["first-line","bipolar-depression","canmat"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT/ISBD 2018 Bipolar Guidelines","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_bipolar_maintenance_lamotrigine_1","stem":"A 35-year-old with bipolar II disorder has predominantly recurrent depressive episodes and few hypomanias. Which agent is best for maintenance to prevent depressive relapse?","options":["Lamotrigine","Valproate / Divalproex","Haloperidol","Bupropion"],"answer":"Lamotrigine","explanation":"Lamotrigine is first-line for bipolar maintenance with predominant depressive polarity — it prevents depressive relapse but is not effective for acute mania. Titrate slowly to avoid SJS/TEN. Valproate targets the manic pole, haloperidol is not a maintenance mood-stabilizer of choice here, and antidepressant monotherapy is inappropriate in bipolar disorder.","meds":["lamotrigine","valproate","haloperidol","bupropion"],"disorder":"Bipolar II disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["maintenance","canmat"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT/ISBD 2018 Bipolar Guidelines","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_bipolar_pregnancy_valproate_1","stem":"A 28-year-old woman with bipolar disorder who is planning pregnancy asks which mood stabilizer should be AVOIDED because of the highest teratogenic risk. Which agent?","options":["Valproate / Divalproex","Lamotrigine","Quetiapine","Lithium"],"answer":"Valproate / Divalproex","explanation":"Valproate carries the highest teratogenic risk — neural tube defects and impaired neurodevelopment/IQ — and is avoided in anyone who could become pregnant. Lamotrigine and quetiapine are comparatively safer options; lithium carries an Ebstein-anomaly signal but a much lower absolute risk than valproate.","meds":["valproate","lamotrigine","quetiapine","lithium"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["special-population","pregnancy","contraindication"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT/ISBD 2018 Bipolar Guidelines","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_serotonin_syndrome_1","stem":"A 52-year-old on phenelzine is inadvertently started on sertraline. Within a day he develops agitation, diaphoresis, hyperthermia, and lower-limb clonus with hyperreflexia. What is the diagnosis?","options":["Serotonin syndrome","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Anticholinergic toxicity","Lithium toxicity"],"answer":"Serotonin syndrome","explanation":"Combining an MAOI with an SSRI causes serotonin syndrome — the triad of neuromuscular excitability (clonus, hyperreflexia), autonomic instability, and altered mental status. Clonus/hyperreflexia distinguish it from NMS (rigidity, hyporeflexia, slower onset). This is why a strict washout is mandatory between MAOIs and serotonergic drugs.","meds":["phenelzine","sertraline"],"disorder":"Serotonin syndrome","difficulty":2,"tags":["serotonin","interaction","washout"],"source":{"name":"Phenelzine/sertraline interactions (deck)","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"va_maoi_tyramine_crisis_1","stem":"A 49-year-old on tranylcypromine eats aged cheese and cured meats at a party and rapidly develops a severe throbbing occipital headache, palpitations, and a blood pressure of 210/120. What is the diagnosis?","options":["Tyramine (hypertensive) crisis","Serotonin syndrome","Anticholinergic toxicity","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome"],"answer":"Tyramine (hypertensive) crisis","explanation":"Irreversible MAOIs block gut/hepatic MAO, so dietary tyramine triggers a surge of noradrenaline release — a hypertensive crisis with occipital headache and palpitations. This is why a strict low-tyramine diet is required. The reversible RIMA moclobemide avoids this because tyramine can displace it from MAO-A.","meds":["tranylcypromine","moclobemide"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["hypertensive-crisis","interaction","diet"],"source":{"name":"Tranylcypromine/MAOI diet (deck)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"va_lithium_toxicity_1","stem":"A 72-year-old woman stable on lithium is started on lisinopril for hypertension and then develops gastroenteritis with poor oral intake. She now has a coarse tremor, ataxia, slurred speech, and confusion. What is the diagnosis?","options":["Lithium toxicity","Serotonin syndrome","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Anticholinergic toxicity"],"answer":"Lithium toxicity","explanation":"ACE inhibitors and volume depletion reduce renal lithium clearance and raise the level; coarse tremor, ataxia, dysarthria, and confusion are hallmark toxicity signs (worse in the elderly with reduced renal reserve). NSAIDs, thiazides, ARBs, and dehydration act the same way — lithium has a narrow therapeutic index (toxic >1.5 mmol/L).","meds":["lithium"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["overdose","interaction","elderly","monitoring"],"source":{"name":"Lithium interactions/warnings (deck)","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ms_mania_mixed_features_valproate","stem":"A 33-year-old man with bipolar I disorder is admitted with a manic episode that carries prominent depressive features, and his chart documents four distinct mood episodes in the past 12 months. The team wants an antimanic agent that can be loaded for rapid control and that performs well in mixed presentations and rapid cycling. Which agent best fits?","options":["Valproate / Divalproex","Lamotrigine","Gabapentin","Topiramate"],"answer":"Valproate / Divalproex","explanation":"Divalproex is a CANMAT/ISBD first-line agent for acute mania, is broad-spectrum for mixed features and rapid cycling, and is the one stabilizer that can be loaded (~20–30 mg/kg/day) for rapid control. Lamotrigine is a maintenance/anti-depressive agent and is not effective for acute mania, while gabapentin and topiramate are not primary mood stabilizers (negative bipolar trials; used for anxiety/sleep/pain and for weight or migraine, respectively).","meds":["valproate","lamotrigine","gabapentin","topiramate"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["acute-mania","mixed-features","rapid-cycling","canmat"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT/ISBD 2018 Bipolar Guidelines","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vd_ms_bipolar2_depression_quetiapine","stem":"A 29-year-old woman with bipolar II disorder presents with a six-week depressive episode marked by anergia and severe initial insomnia. She has never taken a mood stabilizer. Which single agent is an appropriate first-line monotherapy for acute bipolar depression here?","options":["Quetiapine","Sertraline","Bupropion","Gabapentin"],"answer":"Quetiapine","explanation":"Quetiapine carries a CANMAT/ISBD first-line position for acute bipolar depression, and its potent H1 sedation also addresses the insomnia. Sertraline and bupropion are first-line for unipolar MDD only — antidepressant monotherapy is not the recommended approach to bipolar depression — and gabapentin has negative bipolar trials and is not a primary mood stabilizer.","meds":["quetiapine","sertraline","bupropion","gabapentin"],"disorder":"Bipolar II disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["bipolar-depression","first-line","canmat"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT/ISBD 2018 Bipolar Guidelines","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vd_ms_antidepressant_monotherapy_switch","stem":"A 27-year-old with known bipolar I disorder stopped all medication a year ago. Presenting to her family physician with low mood, she is started on sertraline alone. Four weeks later she is euphoric and grandiose, sleeping three hours a night, and has spent $14,000 on a business scheme. Which prescribed medication most likely precipitated this presentation?","options":["Sertraline","Lithium","Quetiapine","Lamotrigine"],"answer":"Sertraline","explanation":"Antidepressant monotherapy in bipolar I disorder risks a switch into mania and is not recommended by CANMAT/ISBD — an antidepressant should only be considered alongside an antimanic mood stabilizer or atypical antipsychotic. Lithium and quetiapine are first-line antimanic agents, and lamotrigine is a maintenance agent for depressive relapse prevention; none of the three precipitates mania.","meds":["sertraline","lithium","quetiapine","lamotrigine"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["switch","bipolar-depression","canmat"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT/ISBD 2018 Bipolar Guidelines","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vd_ms_lithium_hyperparathyroidism","stem":"A 54-year-old woman maintained on a mood stabilizer for nine years reports fatigue, constipation, and low mood. Routine bloodwork shows an elevated corrected serum calcium with an inappropriately non-suppressed PTH; renal function and TSH are stable. Which agent best explains this finding?","options":["Lithium","Valproate / Divalproex","Lamotrigine","Quetiapine"],"answer":"Lithium","explanation":"Lithium's chronic organ toxicity clusters at the kidney, thyroid, and parathyroid — hyperparathyroidism with hypercalcemia is a recognized serious adverse effect, which is precisely why serum calcium joins renal function and TSH at baseline and every 6–12 months thereafter. Valproate (hepatic/pancreatic/haematologic), lamotrigine (dermatologic), and quetiapine (metabolic) do not cause hypercalcemia.","meds":["lithium","valproate","lamotrigine","quetiapine"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":3,"tags":["monitoring","endocrine"],"source":{"name":"openFDA/DailyMed lithium label — warnings and precautions","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ms_lithium_nephrogenic_di","stem":"A 38-year-old man on lithium maintenance for six years passes about five litres of dilute urine daily and is constantly thirsty. Serum sodium is high-normal, urine osmolality is inappropriately low, and there is no improvement in urine concentration after a trial of desmopressin. What is the diagnosis?","options":["Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus","Central diabetes insipidus","Primary polydipsia","SIADH"],"answer":"Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus","explanation":"Lithium blocks the action of ADH at the collecting duct, producing a nephrogenic diabetes insipidus that — unlike central DI — does not respond to desmopressin; amiloride is the pharmacologic answer. Primary polydipsia would not produce a rising sodium, and SIADH causes hyponatremia with concentrated urine, the opposite picture.","meds":["lithium"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":3,"tags":["monitoring","renal","recognise-the-syndrome"],"source":{"name":"openFDA/DailyMed lithium label — warnings and precautions","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ms_lithium_metronidazole_toxicity","stem":"A 46-year-old man has been stable on lithium 900 mg daily for years, with trough levels around 0.8 mmol/L. His dentist starts metronidazole for a dental abscess. Nine days later he has a coarse tremor, ataxia, slurred speech, vomiting, and confusion; his 12-hour trough is now 2.3 mmol/L. Which medication's serum concentration did the antibiotic raise to cause this?","options":["Lithium","Valproate / Divalproex","Lamotrigine","Carbamazepine"],"answer":"Lithium","explanation":"Lithium is not metabolized at all — it is excreted unchanged by the kidney, so metronidazole (like NSAIDs, thiazides, ACE inhibitors/ARBs, and dehydration) reduces its renal clearance and pushes the level from a therapeutic 0.6–1.2 mmol/L into the toxic range (toxicity begins above ~1.5, severe above 2.0). Hold the lithium and restore volume and sodium; hemodialysis is reserved for severe intoxication (e.g., level >4, or >2.5 with symptoms or renal failure). Valproate, lamotrigine, and carbamazepine are hepatically cleared and are unaffected in this way.","meds":["lithium","valproate","lamotrigine","carbamazepine"],"disorder":"Lithium toxicity","difficulty":3,"tags":["interaction","toxicity","monitoring","overdose"],"source":{"name":"openFDA/DailyMed lithium label — drug interactions/overdosage","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ms_lactation_lithium_infant_monitoring","stem":"A 31-year-old woman with bipolar disorder is two weeks postpartum, euthymic on maintenance pharmacotherapy, and strongly wishes to breastfeed. Which of these maintenance agents has traditionally been discouraged during breastfeeding and, if continued, requires monitoring of the infant's serum levels, TSH, and hydration status?","options":["Lithium","Valproate / Divalproex","Lamotrigine","Quetiapine"],"answer":"Lithium","explanation":"Lithium is excreted into breast milk and has traditionally been discouraged in lactation; it can be continued with close infant monitoring of levels, thyroid function, and hydration. Valproate has low milk transfer and is generally considered compatible with breastfeeding (in stark contrast to its pregnancy risk), lamotrigine passes into milk but is usable with infant monitoring, and quetiapine has a low relative infant dose requiring only monitoring for infant sedation.","meds":["lithium","valproate","lamotrigine","quetiapine"],"disorder":"Bipolar disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["lactation","pregnancy","special-population"],"source":{"name":"Deck lactation fields (lithium, valproate, lamotrigine, quetiapine)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vd_ms_valproate_pancreatitis","stem":"A 29-year-old woman with bipolar I disorder, eight weeks into divalproex therapy, presents with severe epigastric pain boring through to her back, persistent vomiting, and a lipase six times the upper limit of normal. Her transaminases and serum ammonia are normal. What has happened?","options":["Acute pancreatitis","Valproate hepatotoxicity","Hyperammonemic encephalopathy","Lithium toxicity"],"answer":"Acute pancreatitis","explanation":"Acute pancreatitis is a recognized serious adverse effect of valproate and, per the label, the drug should ordinarily be discontinued. Valproate hepatotoxicity — most likely in the first six months — presents with malaise, anorexia, vomiting, and deranged liver enzymes rather than an isolated lipase rise, and hyperammonemic encephalopathy presents with lethargy and confusion (classically with normal LFTs) rather than abdominal pain.","meds":["valproate","lithium"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["adverse-effect","recognise-the-syndrome","monitoring"],"source":{"name":"openFDA/DailyMed divalproex label — warnings and precautions","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ms_lamotrigine_sjs_with_valproate","stem":"A 23-year-old with bipolar II disorder taking divalproex has lamotrigine added, but it is started at 25 mg once daily rather than the reduced schedule required with valproate. Three weeks later he develops fever, painful oral and conjunctival ulceration, and a spreading dusky rash with blistering and skin sloughing. What is the diagnosis?","options":["Stevens–Johnson syndrome","DRESS","Serotonin syndrome","Acute pancreatitis"],"answer":"Stevens–Johnson syndrome","explanation":"Valproate inhibits lamotrigine's glucuronidation and roughly doubles its level, so lamotrigine must be halved to 25 mg every other day when the two are combined; a full-dose start plus that interaction is the classic setup for Stevens–Johnson syndrome/TEN, and lamotrigine must be stopped immediately. DRESS is the other lamotrigine hypersensitivity syndrome but presents with eosinophilia and multi-organ involvement rather than mucosal blistering and epidermal detachment.","meds":["lamotrigine","valproate"],"disorder":"Bipolar II disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["rash","interaction","sjs","recognise-the-syndrome"],"source":{"name":"openFDA/DailyMed lamotrigine label — boxed warning (serious skin rashes)","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ms_lamotrigine_missed_doses_retitrate","stem":"A 34-year-old on 200 mg daily of maintenance therapy for bipolar II disorder returns from a three-week trip during which she ran out of her medication and took none for the last 10 days. She feels well and asks to simply resume her usual 200 mg dose tomorrow. Which agent's dosing rules make that unsafe, requiring a full restart of the original titration?","options":["Lamotrigine","Lithium","Valproate / Divalproex","Quetiapine"],"answer":"Lamotrigine","explanation":"Lamotrigine's slow titration exists specifically to prevent Stevens–Johnson syndrome/TEN, and tolerance to that risk is lost after a gap; if doses are missed for more than five days the schedule must be restarted from 25 mg daily and re-escalated. Lithium, divalproex, and quetiapine carry no equivalent re-titration rule — lithium instead needs a repeat 12-hour trough about five days after any dose change.","meds":["lamotrigine","lithium","valproate","quetiapine"],"disorder":"Bipolar II disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["titration","sjs","adherence"],"source":{"name":"openFDA/DailyMed lamotrigine label — dosage and administration","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ms_carbamazepine_hyponatremia_elderly","stem":"A 71-year-old man started on a mood stabilizer six weeks ago is brought in with new confusion, unsteadiness, and a fall. He is clinically euvolemic; serum sodium is 124 mmol/L with inappropriately concentrated urine, and his TSH and cortisol are normal. Which agent is the most likely cause?","options":["Carbamazepine","Lithium","Lamotrigine","Valproate / Divalproex"],"answer":"Carbamazepine","explanation":"Carbamazepine causes SIADH with clinically significant hyponatremia, and the risk is highest in older patients — which is why serum sodium belongs in both the baseline workup and periodic monitoring alongside CBC and LFTs. Lithium does the reverse (hyponatremia raises the lithium level rather than being caused by it), and neither lamotrigine nor valproate is a recognized cause of SIADH.","meds":["carbamazepine","lithium","lamotrigine","valproate"],"disorder":"Bipolar disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["hyponatremia","geriatric","monitoring"],"source":{"name":"openFDA/DailyMed carbamazepine label — warnings and precautions","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vd_ms_carbamazepine_hla_b1502","stem":"A 28-year-old man of Han Chinese ancestry with bipolar disorder is about to start a mood stabilizer. Before the first dose, which agent specifically requires HLA-B*1502 genotyping because carrying that allele confers a strongly increased risk of Stevens–Johnson syndrome and toxic epidermal necrolysis?","options":["Carbamazepine","Lamotrigine","Lithium","Valproate / Divalproex"],"answer":"Carbamazepine","explanation":"Carbamazepine's boxed warning ties SJS/TEN to HLA-B*1502, an allele found almost exclusively in patients of Asian ancestry, so genotyping is part of the baseline workup in that population (HLA-A*3101 instead predicts DRESS). Lamotrigine also causes SJS/TEN, but its risk is managed by slow titration rather than by any HLA screening; lithium and valproate carry no such pharmacogenetic requirement.","meds":["carbamazepine","lamotrigine","lithium","valproate"],"disorder":"Bipolar disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["pharmacogenetics","sjs","monitoring"],"source":{"name":"openFDA/DailyMed carbamazepine label — boxed warning (HLA-B*1502)","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vp_scz_first_line_metabolic","stem":"A 23-year-old man with a first episode of schizophrenia, no prior antipsychotic exposure and a family history of type 2 diabetes, is anxious about weight gain. Which agent best balances efficacy with a weight- and prolactin-neutral profile as an initial choice?","options":["Aripiprazole","Olanzapine","Clozapine","Chlorpromazine"],"answer":"Aripiprazole","explanation":"Aripiprazole is a D2 partial agonist that is essentially weight- and prolactin-neutral, making it a sensible first-episode choice when metabolic risk matters. Olanzapine has the worst metabolic burden of the mainstream SGAs; clozapine is reserved for treatment resistance; chlorpromazine is a sedating, anticholinergic low-potency FGA.","meds":["aripiprazole","olanzapine","clozapine","chlorpromazine"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line","metabolic"],"source":{"name":"CPA Schizophrenia Guidelines","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vp_scz_trs_clozapine","stem":"A 29-year-old with schizophrenia has had persistent positive symptoms despite adequate trials (dose and duration) of risperidone and then olanzapine. Adherence is confirmed. What is the next best pharmacologic step?","options":["Clozapine","Haloperidol","Quetiapine","Benztropine"],"answer":"Clozapine","explanation":"Failure of two adequate antipsychotic trials defines treatment-resistant schizophrenia, for which clozapine is the only agent with proven superior efficacy (and the only one shown to reduce suicidality). Switching to another standard antipsychotic or adding an anticholinergic does not address resistance.","meds":["clozapine","risperidone","olanzapine","haloperidol","quetiapine","benztropine"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":1,"tags":["treatment-resistant","clozapine"],"source":{"name":"Clozapine monograph / CPA Schizophrenia Guidelines","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vp_scz_clozapine_myocarditis","stem":"A patient in the third week of clozapine titration develops fever, pleuritic chest pain, tachycardia, and a rising troponin and CRP. Which clozapine-associated complication is most likely?","options":["Myocarditis","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Agranulocytosis","Pulmonary embolism"],"answer":"Myocarditis","explanation":"Clozapine-induced myocarditis clusters in the first 6–8 weeks and presents with fever, chest pain, tachycardia, and rising troponin/CRP (± eosinophilia). It is distinct from the blood dyscrasia (agranulocytosis) and from NMS, and warrants stopping clozapine.","meds":["clozapine"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":2,"tags":["clozapine","syndrome-id"],"source":{"name":"Clozapine boxed warning / monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vp_scz_clozapine_agranulocytosis","stem":"A patient on clozapine for 8 weeks presents with fever and a severe sore throat. The absolute neutrophil count is 300/µL. Which adverse effect does this represent?","options":["Agranulocytosis","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Myocarditis","Metabolic syndrome"],"answer":"Agranulocytosis","explanation":"An ANC of 300/µL is severe neutropenia/agranulocytosis — clozapine must be stopped immediately (and not rechallenged) with hematology involvement, because of the risk of fatal infection. This mandatory ANC monitoring is why clozapine is reserved despite its efficacy.","meds":["clozapine"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":2,"tags":["clozapine","agranulocytosis","syndrome-id"],"source":{"name":"Clozapine boxed warning / monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vp_scz_clozapine_fluvoxamine","stem":"A patient stable on clozapine needs an antidepressant added for comorbid depression. Which co-prescription is most likely to raise clozapine levels and precipitate toxicity (sedation, seizures)?","options":["Fluvoxamine","Sertraline","Escitalopram","Bupropion"],"answer":"Fluvoxamine","explanation":"Fluvoxamine is a potent CYP1A2 inhibitor and clozapine is a major CYP1A2 substrate, so co-prescription can markedly increase clozapine levels and seizure/toxicity risk. (Conversely, smoking cessation removes CYP1A2 induction and also raises levels.)","meds":["clozapine","fluvoxamine","sertraline","escitalopram","bupropion"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":3,"tags":["clozapine","interaction"],"source":{"name":"Clozapine monograph (CYP1A2 interactions)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vp_scz_metabolic_diabetes","stem":"A 45-year-old with schizophrenia has obesity and poorly controlled type 2 diabetes. You want maintenance antipsychotic therapy with the least metabolic impact. Which is most appropriate?","options":["Lurasidone","Olanzapine","Clozapine","Chlorpromazine"],"answer":"Lurasidone","explanation":"Lurasidone is among the most metabolically favourable SGAs (largely weight-, lipid-, and glucose-neutral) — remembering it must be taken with ≥350 kcal of food for absorption. Olanzapine and clozapine carry the highest metabolic burden, and low-potency FGAs like chlorpromazine also cause weight gain.","meds":["lurasidone","olanzapine","clozapine","chlorpromazine"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":2,"tags":["metabolic"],"source":{"name":"Lurasidone monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vp_scz_lai_adherence","stem":"A 34-year-old with schizophrenia has had three relapse hospitalizations driven by covert non-adherence to oral medication. He responds to and tolerates an SGA. What is the best strategy to improve adherence?","options":["Paliperidone","Quetiapine","Lurasidone","Clozapine"],"answer":"Paliperidone","explanation":"Paliperidone palmitate is a long-acting injectable, directly addressing covert non-adherence and reducing relapse. Quetiapine, lurasidone, and clozapine are oral-only in Canada (clozapine is also reserved for treatment resistance).","meds":["paliperidone","quetiapine","lurasidone","clozapine"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":2,"tags":["lai","adherence"],"source":{"name":"Paliperidone palmitate monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vp_agit_olanzapine_benzo","stem":"An acutely agitated psychotic patient in the emergency department is being managed with intramuscular medication. Co-administering a parenteral benzodiazepine with which antipsychotic carries a specific risk of cardiorespiratory depression and should be avoided?","options":["Olanzapine","Haloperidol","Ziprasidone","Aripiprazole"],"answer":"Olanzapine","explanation":"Intramuscular olanzapine combined with a parenteral benzodiazepine has caused excessive sedation and cardiorespiratory depression, so the combination is avoided (separate the doses). IM haloperidol is routinely combined with lorazepam, and the other agents do not carry this specific warning.","meds":["olanzapine","haloperidol","ziprasidone","aripiprazole","lorazepam"],"disorder":"Acute agitation","difficulty":2,"tags":["agitation","interaction"],"source":{"name":"Olanzapine monograph (IM warning)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vp_delirium_haloperidol","stem":"An 80-year-old post-operative patient has hyperactive delirium with severe agitation that threatens lines and safety despite non-pharmacologic measures. Which pharmacologic agent is most appropriate for short-term control?","options":["Haloperidol","Lorazepam","Quetiapine","Chlorpromazine"],"answer":"Haloperidol","explanation":"When medication is unavoidable for dangerous agitation in delirium, a low-dose high-potency antipsychotic such as haloperidol is preferred. Benzodiazepines can worsen or prolong delirium (reserved for alcohol/sedative withdrawal), and chlorpromazine's hypotension and anticholinergic load are poorly tolerated in the elderly.","meds":["haloperidol","lorazepam","quetiapine","chlorpromazine"],"disorder":"Delirium","difficulty":2,"tags":["delirium","elderly"],"source":{"name":"Delirium management (authored)","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vp_delirium_etoh_withdrawal","stem":"A 55-year-old admitted 48 hours after his last drink becomes agitated and confused with tremor, diaphoresis, tachycardia, and hypertension. Which is the first-line pharmacologic treatment for this delirium?","options":["Lorazepam","Haloperidol","Olanzapine","Risperidone"],"answer":"Lorazepam","explanation":"This is alcohol-withdrawal delirium (delirium tremens), for which a benzodiazepine such as lorazepam is first-line and lifesaving. Antipsychotics lower the seizure threshold and are only adjuncts here — the opposite of the approach to a general medical/post-operative delirium.","meds":["lorazepam","haloperidol","olanzapine","risperidone"],"disorder":"Delirium","difficulty":2,"tags":["delirium","withdrawal"],"source":{"name":"Alcohol withdrawal management (authored)","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vp_bpsd_risperidone","stem":"An 82-year-old with Alzheimer dementia has persistent aggression and psychosis endangering caregivers despite behavioural interventions. After discussing the increased mortality risk, a short low-dose antipsychotic trial is chosen. Which agent has the best evidence for short-term severe aggression in dementia?","options":["Risperidone","Clozapine","Ziprasidone","Chlorpromazine"],"answer":"Risperidone","explanation":"Low-dose risperidone is the best-studied option (with a limited short-term indication for severe aggression) in dementia, though all antipsychotics carry a boxed warning for increased mortality and cerebrovascular events — use the lowest dose for the shortest time. Clozapine (agranulocytosis monitoring) and sedating/anticholinergic FGAs are inappropriate in this population.","meds":["risperidone","clozapine","ziprasidone","chlorpromazine"],"disorder":"Major neurocognitive disorder (dementia)","difficulty":2,"tags":["bpsd","elderly"],"source":{"name":"Risperidone monograph (dementia warning)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vp_pd_psychosis_pimavanserin","stem":"A 74-year-old with Parkinson disease develops distressing visual hallucinations. Dopaminergic therapy is already minimized. Which agent treats the psychosis with the least risk of worsening his motor symptoms?","options":["Pimavanserin","Haloperidol","Risperidone","Olanzapine"],"answer":"Pimavanserin","explanation":"Pimavanserin is a selective 5-HT2A inverse agonist with no D2 blockade, so it treats Parkinson-disease psychosis without worsening motor function (low-dose quetiapine or clozapine are the usual Canadian alternatives). D2 blockers such as haloperidol, risperidone, and olanzapine aggravate parkinsonism and are avoided.","meds":["pimavanserin","haloperidol","risperidone","olanzapine","quetiapine","clozapine"],"disorder":"Parkinson disease psychosis","difficulty":3,"tags":["pd-psychosis","eps"],"source":{"name":"Pimavanserin monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vp_eps_acute_dystonia_tx","stem":"A 19-year-old man given intramuscular haloperidol for agitation develops, a few hours later, painful neck twisting (torticollis) and an upward fixed gaze (oculogyric crisis). What is the best immediate treatment?","options":["Benztropine","Propranolol","Tetrabenazine","Valbenazine"],"answer":"Benztropine","explanation":"Acute dystonia (young men, high-potency FGAs, within hours) responds rapidly to an intramuscular anticholinergic such as benztropine (or diphenhydramine). Propranolol treats akathisia, and VMAT2 inhibitors (tetrabenazine, valbenazine) are for tardive dyskinesia.","meds":["benztropine","propranolol","tetrabenazine","valbenazine","haloperidol"],"disorder":"Extrapyramidal symptoms","difficulty":1,"tags":["eps","dystonia"],"source":{"name":"Benztropine monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vp_eps_dystonia_syndrome_id","stem":"Hours after his first dose of a high-potency antipsychotic, a young patient develops sustained involuntary contraction of the neck and jaw muscles with an upward eye deviation. Which movement syndrome is this?","options":["Acute dystonia","Tardive dyskinesia","Akathisia","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome"],"answer":"Acute dystonia","explanation":"Sustained, painful muscle contractions (torticollis, oculogyric crisis, trismus, potentially laryngospasm) appearing within hours to days of a D2 blocker define acute dystonia. It is distinct from the choreoathetoid movements of tardive dyskinesia, the restlessness of akathisia, and the rigidity/fever of NMS.","meds":["haloperidol","benztropine"],"disorder":"Extrapyramidal symptoms","difficulty":2,"tags":["eps","dystonia","syndrome-id"],"source":{"name":"EPS recognition (authored)","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vp_eps_akathisia_propranolol","stem":"One week after starting an antipsychotic, a patient reports an intolerable inner restlessness and an inability to sit still, and is observed pacing and shifting constantly. After considering a dose reduction, which is the best-evidenced pharmacologic treatment?","options":["Propranolol","Benztropine","Tetrabenazine","Amantadine"],"answer":"Propranolol","explanation":"Antipsychotic-induced akathisia responds best to a beta-blocker such as propranolol (± lowering the antipsychotic dose or a short benzodiazepine course). Anticholinergics like benztropine do not reliably relieve akathisia, and dopamine-depleting VMAT2 inhibitors are for tardive dyskinesia.","meds":["propranolol","benztropine","tetrabenazine","amantadine"],"disorder":"Extrapyramidal symptoms","difficulty":2,"tags":["eps","akathisia"],"source":{"name":"Propranolol monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vp_eps_td_syndrome_id","stem":"A 68-year-old who has taken an antipsychotic for several years develops persistent involuntary lip-smacking, tongue protrusion, and choreoathetoid facial movements that are absent during sleep. Which syndrome is this?","options":["Tardive dyskinesia","Acute dystonia","Akathisia","Drug-induced parkinsonism"],"answer":"Tardive dyskinesia","explanation":"Late-onset, repetitive orofacial-lingual choreoathetoid movements after prolonged D2 blockade define tardive dyskinesia. It contrasts with the acute sustained spasm of dystonia, the subjective restlessness of akathisia, and the bradykinesia/rigidity/tremor of drug-induced parkinsonism.","meds":["haloperidol","tetrabenazine"],"disorder":"Tardive dyskinesia","difficulty":2,"tags":["eps","tardive-dyskinesia","syndrome-id"],"source":{"name":"EPS recognition (authored)","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vp_eps_td_tx","stem":"A patient has established tardive dyskinesia with troublesome orofacial movements after years of antipsychotic therapy. Which class of agent is the evidence-based treatment?","options":["Tetrabenazine","Benztropine","Trihexyphenidyl","Propranolol"],"answer":"Tetrabenazine","explanation":"Tardive dyskinesia is treated with a VMAT2 inhibitor — tetrabenazine is the Canada-available option (the purpose-built agents valbenazine and deutetrabenazine are US-approved for TD). Anticholinergics such as benztropine and trihexyphenidyl actually WORSEN tardive dyskinesia, and propranolol targets akathisia.","meds":["tetrabenazine","benztropine","trihexyphenidyl","propranolol","valbenazine","deutetrabenazine"],"disorder":"Tardive dyskinesia","difficulty":2,"tags":["eps","tardive-dyskinesia"],"source":{"name":"Tetrabenazine monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vp_eps_parkinsonism_amantadine","stem":"A patient on an antipsychotic develops bradykinesia, cogwheel rigidity, and a resting tremor consistent with drug-induced parkinsonism. Antipsychotic dose reduction is not fully sufficient. Which adjunct is appropriate, and which class must be avoided because it would worsen the picture?","options":["Amantadine","Tetrabenazine","Valbenazine","Propranolol"],"answer":"Amantadine","explanation":"Drug-induced parkinsonism is managed by reducing/switching the antipsychotic and, if needed, an anticholinergic or the dopaminergic agent amantadine. VMAT2 inhibitors (tetrabenazine, valbenazine) deplete dopamine and would aggravate parkinsonism, and propranolol does not treat it.","meds":["amantadine","tetrabenazine","valbenazine","propranolol"],"disorder":"Extrapyramidal symptoms","difficulty":2,"tags":["eps","parkinsonism"],"source":{"name":"Amantadine monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vp_nms_recognition","stem":"Three days after starting haloperidol, a patient develops a temperature of 40°C, generalized 'lead-pipe' rigidity, fluctuating consciousness, labile blood pressure and tachycardia, and a markedly elevated creatine kinase. What is the diagnosis?","options":["Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Serotonin syndrome","Malignant hyperthermia","Anticholinergic toxicity"],"answer":"Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","explanation":"Hyperthermia, lead-pipe rigidity, altered mental status, autonomic instability, and a high CK developing over days after a D2 blocker are the classic tetrad of NMS. Serotonin syndrome instead shows clonus/hyperreflexia with rapid onset after serotonergic drugs; anticholinergic toxicity gives dry, flushed skin without rigidity or CK elevation.","meds":["haloperidol"],"disorder":"Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","difficulty":2,"tags":["nms","syndrome-id"],"source":{"name":"NMS recognition (authored)","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vp_nms_culprit","stem":"Which of the following antipsychotics carries the highest risk of precipitating neuroleptic malignant syndrome?","options":["Haloperidol","Quetiapine","Clozapine","Aripiprazole"],"answer":"Haloperidol","explanation":"NMS risk rises with potent, tight D2 blockade, so high-potency FGAs such as haloperidol carry the greatest risk (especially with rapid dose escalation or parenteral use). Loosely-binding or partial-agonist agents like quetiapine, clozapine, and aripiprazole carry lower — though not zero — risk.","meds":["haloperidol","quetiapine","clozapine","aripiprazole"],"disorder":"Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","difficulty":2,"tags":["nms"],"source":{"name":"Antipsychotic monographs (NMS)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vp_hyperprolactinemia_switch","stem":"A 26-year-old woman on risperidone develops amenorrhea and galactorrhea; her prolactin is markedly elevated with no pituitary lesion on imaging. Which switch best addresses the hyperprolactinemia?","options":["Aripiprazole","Paliperidone","Haloperidol","Fluphenazine"],"answer":"Aripiprazole","explanation":"Risperidone (and its metabolite paliperidone) cause the most marked hyperprolactinemia among antipsychotics. Switching to the prolactin-sparing partial agonist aripiprazole typically normalizes prolactin, whereas high-potency FGAs like haloperidol and fluphenazine raise it further.","meds":["aripiprazole","paliperidone","haloperidol","fluphenazine","risperidone"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":2,"tags":["hyperprolactinemia"],"source":{"name":"Aripiprazole / risperidone monographs","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vp_qt_ziprasidone","stem":"A patient with congenital long-QT syndrome and a baseline QTc of 480 ms needs an antipsychotic. Which agent is most important to AVOID because it carries the greatest QT-prolonging risk among the SGAs?","options":["Ziprasidone","Aripiprazole","Lurasidone","Brexpiprazole"],"answer":"Ziprasidone","explanation":"Ziprasidone produces the greatest QTc prolongation of the SGAs and should be avoided when the QT is already long. Aripiprazole, lurasidone, and brexpiprazole are comparatively QT-neutral and are safer choices in this setting.","meds":["ziprasidone","aripiprazole","lurasidone","brexpiprazole"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":2,"tags":["qt"],"source":{"name":"Ziprasidone monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vt_recognise_serotonin_syndrome_1","stem":"A 40-year-old on sertraline for depression is given tramadol for back pain. Over ~12 hours he develops agitation, diaphoresis, tachycardia, hyperthermia, and — on exam — inducible lower-limb clonus and hyperreflexia worse in the legs. Most likely syndrome?","options":["Serotonin syndrome","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Anticholinergic toxicity","Lithium toxicity"],"answer":"Serotonin syndrome","explanation":"Rapid onset (hours) with NEUROMUSCULAR EXCITABILITY — clonus and hyperreflexia, lower-limb predominant — after adding a second serotonergic (tramadol to an SSRI) is the signature of serotonin syndrome. NMS instead evolves over days with lead-pipe rigidity and hyporeflexia; anticholinergic toxicity gives dry skin and normal reflexes; lithium toxicity gives a coarse tremor and ataxia, not clonus.","meds":["sertraline"],"disorder":"Serotonin syndrome","difficulty":2,"tags":["serotonin","interaction"],"source":{"name":"FRCPC toxidrome recognition (Hunter criteria)","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vt_recognise_nms_1","stem":"A 28-year-old admitted with mania is started on haloperidol. Four days later he is febrile (39.5°C), profoundly diaphoretic, with generalised 'lead-pipe' rigidity, hyporeflexia, fluctuating consciousness, labile blood pressure, and CK 6000. Most likely syndrome?","options":["Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Serotonin syndrome","Anticholinergic toxicity","Hypertensive crisis (tyramine reaction)"],"answer":"Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","explanation":"Sub-acute onset (days) after a dopamine antagonist, with lead-pipe rigidity, HYPOreflexia, hyperthermia, autonomic instability, and markedly elevated CK, defines NMS. Serotonin syndrome is faster and features clonus/hyperreflexia rather than hyporeflexia; anticholinergic toxicity lacks rigidity and CK rise; a tyramine reaction is an acute hypertensive event without rigidity.","meds":["haloperidol"],"disorder":"Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","difficulty":2,"tags":["nms"],"source":{"name":"FRCPC toxidrome recognition","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vt_ss_vs_nms_discriminator_1","stem":"A patient stabilised on olanzapine has sertraline added 2 days ago and now presents with hyperthermia, agitation, tremor, and — critically — spontaneous ocular clonus and brisk hyperreflexia rather than rigidity. Which single exam finding best distinguishes his diagnosis from neuroleptic malignant syndrome?","options":["Serotonin syndrome","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Anticholinergic toxicity","Lithium toxicity"],"answer":"Serotonin syndrome","explanation":"Clonus and hyperreflexia point to serotonin syndrome (here precipitated by the newly added serotonergic), whereas NMS produces lead-pipe RIGIDITY with hyporeflexia. Onset also helps: serotonin syndrome is hours, NMS is days. The distinction drives management — cyproheptadine and stopping serotonergics versus dantrolene/bromocriptine and stopping the antipsychotic.","meds":["sertraline","olanzapine"],"disorder":"Serotonin syndrome","difficulty":3,"tags":["serotonin","nms","interaction"],"source":{"name":"FRCPC toxidrome discriminator","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vt_recognise_anticholinergic_toxidrome_1","stem":"A 19-year-old is brought in after ingesting a bottle of amitriptyline. She is delirious and agitated with dilated pupils, dry flushed skin, absent bowel sounds, urinary retention, and tachycardia; the ECG shows a widening QRS. Which toxidrome best explains the peripheral findings?","options":["Anticholinergic toxicity","Serotonin syndrome","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Lithium toxicity"],"answer":"Anticholinergic toxicity","explanation":"The classic anticholinergic toxidrome — 'mad, blind, dry, red, hot, and full' (delirium, mydriasis, dry/flushed skin, ileus, urinary retention, hyperthermia) — is prominent in TCA overdose. Note the co-existing life-threat: Na-channel-blockade cardiotoxicity (wide QRS) is what actually kills in amitriptyline overdose and is treated with IV sodium bicarbonate for QRS >100 ms.","meds":["amitriptyline"],"disorder":"Anticholinergic toxicity","difficulty":2,"tags":["overdose"],"source":{"name":"Amitriptyline monograph — overdose","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vt_recognise_lithium_toxicity_1","stem":"A 55-year-old on long-term lithium for bipolar I develops a coarse tremor, unsteady gait, slurred speech, and confusion over several days. Her GP recently started hydrochlorothiazide for hypertension. Most likely syndrome?","options":["Lithium toxicity","Serotonin syndrome","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Anticholinergic toxicity"],"answer":"Lithium toxicity","explanation":"Coarse tremor, ataxia, dysarthria, and confusion are hallmark lithium toxicity; a thiazide (like NSAIDs and ACEi/ARBs) reduces renal lithium clearance and raises the level. Toxicity begins around >1.5 mmol/L and is severe >2.0; hemodialysis is indicated for levels >4, or >2.5 with symptoms/renal failure.","meds":["lithium"],"disorder":"Lithium toxicity","difficulty":2,"tags":["interaction","monitoring"],"source":{"name":"Lithium monograph — toxicity/DDI","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vt_recognise_tyramine_crisis_1","stem":"A 47-year-old on phenelzine for treatment-resistant depression eats aged cheddar and cured salami at a party and within an hour develops a severe pounding occipital headache, blood pressure 220/125, palpitations, and neck stiffness. Most likely syndrome?","options":["Hypertensive crisis (tyramine reaction)","Serotonin syndrome","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Lithium toxicity"],"answer":"Hypertensive crisis (tyramine reaction)","explanation":"MAO inhibition prevents breakdown of dietary tyramine, causing a surge of norepinephrine release — the tyramine 'cheese reaction' with abrupt occipital headache and dangerous hypertension. It requires a strict low-tyramine diet (avoid aged cheese, cured/fermented meats, fermented soy, tap beer, and yeast extracts). It is a pressor crisis, not the neuromuscular picture of serotonin syndrome.","meds":["phenelzine"],"disorder":"Hypertensive crisis (tyramine reaction)","difficulty":2,"tags":["interaction"],"source":{"name":"Phenelzine monograph — tyramine reaction","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vt_ddi_fluvoxamine_clozapine_1a2_1","stem":"A patient stable on clozapine for treatment-resistant schizophrenia develops comorbid OCD and needs an SSRI. Which SSRI is the most dangerous to add because it will sharply raise the clozapine level and risk seizures/toxicity?","options":["Fluvoxamine","Sertraline","Escitalopram","Citalopram"],"answer":"Fluvoxamine","explanation":"Fluvoxamine is a potent CYP1A2 inhibitor and clozapine is a 1A2 substrate, so co-prescription can multiply clozapine levels and precipitate seizures, sedation, and cardiotoxicity. Sertraline, escitalopram, or citalopram are far safer 1A2-sparing choices. (The same 1A2 axis explains why stopping smoking also raises clozapine levels.)","meds":["fluvoxamine","clozapine","sertraline","escitalopram"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":2,"tags":["interaction"],"source":{"name":"Fluvoxamine/clozapine monograph — CYP1A2","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vt_ddi_maoi_meperidine_1","stem":"A 50-year-old maintained on phenelzine needs post-operative analgesia. The surgical team orders meperidine (pethidine). Shortly after the dose she becomes hyperthermic and agitated with clonus and rigidity. What syndrome has the MAOI + meperidine combination precipitated?","options":["Serotonin syndrome","Anticholinergic toxicity","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Hypertensive crisis (tyramine reaction)"],"answer":"Serotonin syndrome","explanation":"Meperidine has serotonergic activity and is explicitly contraindicated with MAOIs — the combination can cause fatal serotonin syndrome. This is a classic 'never' interaction: MAOIs must be kept away from meperidine, SSRIs/SNRIs/TCAs, tramadol, dextromethorphan, and linezolid, with a 14-day washout each way (5 weeks after fluoxetine).","meds":["phenelzine"],"disorder":"Serotonin syndrome","difficulty":2,"tags":["serotonin","interaction"],"source":{"name":"Phenelzine monograph — contraindicated combos","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vt_ddi_valproate_lamotrigine_1","stem":"A patient on lamotrigine maintenance for bipolar II is about to have a mood stabilizer added. Which agent roughly DOUBLES the lamotrigine level by inhibiting its glucuronidation, mandating that the lamotrigine dose be halved to reduce serious-rash risk?","options":["Valproate","Carbamazepine","Lithium","Gabapentin"],"answer":"Valproate","explanation":"Valproate inhibits lamotrigine glucuronidation and roughly doubles its level, sharply increasing the risk of Stevens–Johnson syndrome/TEN — so the lamotrigine dose is halved and titrated even more slowly. Carbamazepine does the opposite (induces glucuronidation and LOWERS lamotrigine); lithium and gabapentin do not have this pharmacokinetic interaction.","meds":["valproate","lamotrigine","carbamazepine","lithium"],"disorder":"Bipolar II disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["interaction"],"source":{"name":"Lamotrigine/valproate monograph — DDI","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vt_ddi_carbamazepine_ocp_1","stem":"A 24-year-old woman with bipolar disorder using a combined oral contraceptive is started on a mood stabilizer, and three months later presents pregnant despite perfect pill adherence. Which drug most likely caused contraceptive failure through enzyme induction?","options":["Carbamazepine","Valproate","Lamotrigine","Lithium"],"answer":"Carbamazepine","explanation":"Carbamazepine is a strong CYP3A4 inducer and lowers estrogen/progestin levels, causing oral-contraceptive failure — a non-hormonal or higher-dose method is required. Valproate, lamotrigine, and lithium do not induce the pill's metabolism (indeed the estrogen in the pill LOWERS lamotrigine levels, the reverse direction).","meds":["carbamazepine","valproate","lamotrigine","lithium"],"disorder":"Bipolar disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["interaction"],"source":{"name":"Carbamazepine monograph — 3A4 induction","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vt_ddi_carbamazepine_autoinduction_1","stem":"A man started on carbamazepine has a therapeutic level at week 1, but by week 4 — on the same dose, with good adherence — his level has fallen below range and seizures/mood symptoms return. Which property of carbamazepine explains this, requiring a level recheck at ~2–4 weeks?","options":["Carbamazepine","Valproate","Lamotrigine","Lithium"],"answer":"Carbamazepine","explanation":"Carbamazepine AUTO-induces its own CYP3A4 metabolism over the first weeks, so a level that was therapeutic can drop despite a stable dose — hence the standard recheck at ~2–4 weeks with dose adjustment. Valproate, lamotrigine, and lithium do not autoinduce in this way.","meds":["carbamazepine","valproate","lamotrigine","lithium"],"disorder":"Bipolar disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["interaction","monitoring"],"source":{"name":"Carbamazepine monograph — autoinduction","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vt_ddi_clozapine_carbamazepine_1","stem":"A patient on clozapine develops trigeminal neuralgia and a consultant suggests a mood stabilizer/anticonvulsant. Which agent is specifically CONTRAINDICATED to combine with clozapine because of additive bone-marrow suppression and agranulocytosis risk?","options":["Carbamazepine","Valproate","Lithium","Lamotrigine"],"answer":"Carbamazepine","explanation":"Carbamazepine can itself cause agranulocytosis/aplastic anemia, so combining it with clozapine (already registry-monitored for neutropenia) is contraindicated — the marrow-suppression risk is additive, compounded by enzyme induction. Valproate, lithium (which can even raise the neutrophil count), or lamotrigine are used instead when a mood stabilizer is needed.","meds":["carbamazepine","clozapine","valproate","lithium"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":2,"tags":["agranulocytosis","interaction"],"source":{"name":"Clozapine monograph — contraindicated combos","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vt_overdose_most_lethal_tca_1","stem":"Four patients each ingest a two-week supply of their antidepressant. Which agent carries the HIGHEST risk of a fatal overdose from wide-QRS ventricular arrhythmia, seizures, and coma?","options":["Amitriptyline","Sertraline","Escitalopram","Fluoxetine"],"answer":"Amitriptyline","explanation":"TCAs like amitriptyline are among the most lethal antidepressants in overdose: sodium-channel blockade causes QRS widening and ventricular arrhythmia plus the 'three C's' (coma, convulsions, cardiotoxicity) and severe anticholinergic toxicity — treated with IV sodium bicarbonate. SSRIs (sertraline, escitalopram, fluoxetine) are comparatively safe in overdose, which is a major reason they are first-line.","meds":["amitriptyline","sertraline","escitalopram","fluoxetine"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["overdose"],"source":{"name":"TCA vs SSRI overdose lethality","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vt_overdose_maoi_vs_ssri_1","stem":"A patient with treatment-resistant depression asks which of her possible antidepressants would be the most dangerous in overdose because of delayed (up to 12–24 h) hyperthermia, autonomic collapse, and a narrow margin. Which one?","options":["Phenelzine","Fluoxetine","Sertraline","Escitalopram"],"answer":"Phenelzine","explanation":"MAOI overdose (phenelzine) is dangerous and often DELAYED — agitation, hyperthermia, autonomic instability, and cardiovascular collapse can appear 12–24 h later, so a reassuring early picture is deceptive. This high lethality (shared with TCAs) contrasts sharply with the relative safety of SSRIs such as fluoxetine, sertraline, or escitalopram.","meds":["phenelzine","fluoxetine","sertraline","escitalopram"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["overdose"],"source":{"name":"Phenelzine monograph — overdose","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vt_overdose_barbiturate_vs_benzo_1","stem":"A patient co-ingests a sedative and presents with profound respiratory depression and coma. Which sedative-hypnotic has NO ceiling effect and the highest overdose lethality, is NOT reversed by flumazenil, and requires airway support and urinary alkalinization?","options":["Phenobarbital","Lorazepam","Diazepam","Zopiclone"],"answer":"Phenobarbital","explanation":"Barbiturates like phenobarbital have a narrow therapeutic index and no ceiling on CNS/respiratory depression, historically a common lethal overdose; management is supportive with multi-dose charcoal and urinary alkalinization, and flumazenil does NOT reverse them. This is the key contrast with benzodiazepines (lorazepam, diazepam) and z-drugs (zopiclone), which are far safer taken alone.","meds":["phenobarbital","lorazepam","diazepam","zopiclone"],"disorder":"Insomnia","difficulty":2,"tags":["overdose"],"source":{"name":"Phenobarbital monograph — overdose","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vt_overdose_lithium_dialysis_1","stem":"A patient with a very narrow-therapeutic-index psychotropic presents obtunded after an overdose; the toxicology team is considering hemodialysis. For which of these is overdose a medical emergency with hemodialysis indicated at a serum level >4 (or >2.5 with symptoms/renal failure)?","options":["Lithium","Sertraline","Lamotrigine","Quetiapine"],"answer":"Lithium","explanation":"Lithium has a narrow therapeutic index and its overdose is a medical emergency; hemodialysis is used for severe intoxication (level >4, or >2.5 with symptoms/renal failure) because dialysis efficiently clears the small ion. Sertraline, lamotrigine, and quetiapine overdoses are managed supportively and rarely require dialysis.","meds":["lithium","sertraline","lamotrigine","quetiapine"],"disorder":"Lithium toxicity","difficulty":2,"tags":["overdose","monitoring"],"source":{"name":"Lithium monograph — overdose/dialysis","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vt_pregnancy_valproate_avoid_1","stem":"A 27-year-old woman with bipolar I who plans to conceive is on a mood stabilizer. Which agent is the MOST teratogenic — causing neural-tube defects, the lowest childhood IQ, and increased autism — and should be avoided in people who can become pregnant?","options":["Valproate","Lamotrigine","Lithium","Carbamazepine"],"answer":"Valproate","explanation":"Valproate is the most teratogenic mood stabilizer: neural-tube defects (spina bifida), craniofacial/cardiac malformations, and dose-dependent neurodevelopmental harm (lowest IQ, increased autism). Carbamazepine also causes neural-tube defects but less severely overall; lamotrigine is a comparatively safer maintenance option, and lithium's main risk is the (lower-than-historically-taught) cardiac malformation.","meds":["valproate","lamotrigine","lithium","carbamazepine"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["pregnancy"],"source":{"name":"Valproate monograph — teratogenicity","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vt_pregnancy_lithium_ebstein_1","stem":"A woman conceives while on maintenance therapy for bipolar disorder. First-trimester exposure to which agent is classically associated with Ebstein anomaly (a tricuspid-valve malformation), warranting fetal echocardiography?","options":["Lithium","Lamotrigine","Sertraline","Bupropion"],"answer":"Lithium","explanation":"First-trimester lithium is linked to Ebstein anomaly (tricuspid malformation), though the absolute risk is lower than historically taught; if continued, monitor levels closely (clearance rises in pregnancy then falls abruptly at delivery) and arrange fetal echocardiography. Lamotrigine, sertraline, and bupropion do not carry the Ebstein association.","meds":["lithium","lamotrigine","sertraline","bupropion"],"disorder":"Bipolar disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["pregnancy"],"source":{"name":"Lithium monograph — pregnancy","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vt_pregnancy_safest_stabilizer_1","stem":"A pregnant woman with bipolar II needs mood-stabilizer maintenance. Which agent has the most reassuring reproductive-safety profile (no consistent major teratogenic signal) and is often preferred, keeping in mind that its levels fall in pregnancy and must be reduced postpartum?","options":["Lamotrigine","Valproate","Carbamazepine","Lithium"],"answer":"Lamotrigine","explanation":"Lamotrigine is comparatively pregnancy-safer with no consistent major teratogenic signal and is often the preferred maintenance stabilizer; its levels fall markedly during pregnancy (may need dose increases) and must be reduced postpartum to avoid toxicity. Valproate and carbamazepine cause neural-tube defects, and lithium carries the Ebstein risk.","meds":["lamotrigine","valproate","carbamazepine","lithium"],"disorder":"Bipolar II disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["pregnancy"],"source":{"name":"Lamotrigine monograph — pregnancy","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vt_pregnancy_paroxetine_avoid_1","stem":"A woman planning pregnancy needs an antidepressant for recurrent MDD. Which SSRI is generally AVOIDED in the first trimester because of an association with fetal cardiac malformations (e.g., septal defects)?","options":["Paroxetine","Sertraline","Escitalopram","Fluoxetine"],"answer":"Paroxetine","explanation":"Paroxetine has been associated with cardiac malformations (e.g., septal defects) and is generally avoided in pregnancy when alternatives exist. Sertraline is a common perinatal first choice; escitalopram and fluoxetine are also reasonable — reflecting CANMAT perinatal guidance to prefer better-studied, lower-risk SSRIs.","meds":["paroxetine","sertraline","escitalopram","fluoxetine"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["pregnancy"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT perinatal 2024 / paroxetine monograph","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"vt_monitor_clozapine_anc_1","stem":"Which antipsychotic requires mandatory, registry-enforced absolute neutrophil count monitoring — weekly for the first 6 months, then every 2 weeks to 12 months, then every 4 weeks — with discontinuation (and generally no rechallenge) if the ANC falls below 0.5 ×10⁹/L?","options":["Clozapine","Olanzapine","Risperidone","Quetiapine"],"answer":"Clozapine","explanation":"Only clozapine carries a mandatory ANC-monitoring registry because of its risk of agranulocytosis: weekly ×6 months, then q2 weeks to 12 months, then q4 weeks; severe neutropenia (ANC <0.5 ×10⁹/L) means discontinue and generally do not rechallenge. Olanzapine, risperidone, and quetiapine have no such hematologic monitoring requirement.","meds":["clozapine","olanzapine","risperidone","quetiapine"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":1,"tags":["agranulocytosis","monitoring"],"source":{"name":"Clozapine monograph — ANC monitoring","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vt_monitor_citalopram_qt_1","stem":"Which SSRI carries a dose-dependent QT-prolongation warning with a maximum-dose ceiling of 40 mg/day (20 mg/day in the elderly or hepatic impairment / CYP2C19 poor metabolizers), and the most QT risk in overdose?","options":["Citalopram","Sertraline","Fluoxetine","Paroxetine"],"answer":"Citalopram","explanation":"Citalopram has a dose-dependent QT-prolongation warning: cap at 40 mg/day (20 mg/day in the elderly, hepatic impairment, or CYP2C19 poor metabolizers), and it prolongs QT more than other SSRIs in overdose (get an ECG in significant ingestion). Its enantiomer escitalopram carries only a mild QT signal; sertraline, fluoxetine, and paroxetine lack this specific ceiling.","meds":["citalopram","sertraline","fluoxetine","paroxetine"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["qt","monitoring"],"source":{"name":"Citalopram monograph — QT warning","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"va_spop_preg_valproate_avoid","stem":"A 26-year-old woman with bipolar I disorder who can become pregnant and does not use reliable contraception needs a mood stabilizer. Which agent should be AVOIDED because it is the most teratogenic (neural-tube defects and the lowest childhood IQ)?","options":["Valproate / Divalproex","Lamotrigine","Lithium","Quetiapine"],"answer":"Valproate / Divalproex","explanation":"Valproate/divalproex is the most teratogenic mood stabilizer — neural-tube defects plus dose-dependent neurodevelopmental harm (lowest childhood IQ, increased autism) — so it is avoided in anyone who can become pregnant. Lamotrigine is comparatively pregnancy-safer, and quetiapine/lithium carry lower structural risk (lithium's concern is Ebstein anomaly).","meds":["valproate","lamotrigine","lithium","quetiapine"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["pregnancy","contraindication"],"source":{"name":"openFDA/monograph valproate label — pregnancy; CANMAT/ISBD 2018","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"va_spop_preg_sertraline_preferred","stem":"A 30-year-old at 8 weeks' gestation has moderate major depression and needs an antidepressant. Considering reproductive-safety data and low breast-milk transfer for continued use during lactation, which SSRI is a preferred first choice?","options":["Sertraline","Paroxetine","Fluvoxamine","Fluoxetine"],"answer":"Sertraline","explanation":"Sertraline is among the preferred SSRIs in pregnancy/lactation given its data and low milk transfer (CANMAT perinatal). Paroxetine is generally avoided (cardiac malformation signal), fluvoxamine has more limited perinatal data, and fluoxetine's very long half-life secretes more into milk.","meds":["sertraline","paroxetine","fluvoxamine","fluoxetine"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["pregnancy","first-line"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT perinatal 2024; deck pregnancy/lactation fields","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_spop_preg_paroxetine_avoid","stem":"A woman planning pregnancy asks which SSRI carries a reported association with fetal cardiac (septal) malformations and is generally avoided in the first trimester. Which agent is she describing?","options":["Paroxetine","Sertraline","Citalopram","Escitalopram"],"answer":"Paroxetine","explanation":"Paroxetine has been associated with cardiac malformations (e.g., septal defects) in some studies and is generally avoided in pregnancy. Sertraline, citalopram, and escitalopram show no consistent major teratogenic signal and are more reasonable perinatal choices.","meds":["paroxetine","sertraline","citalopram","escitalopram"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["pregnancy","contraindication"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT perinatal 2024; deck paroxetine pregnancy field","origin":"canmat"}},{"id":"va_spop_preg_lithium_ebstein","stem":"A 28-year-old with bipolar I who wants to continue a mood stabilizer through the first trimester should be counselled about a small increased risk of a specific cardiac malformation (Ebstein anomaly) and offered fetal echocardiography. Which drug carries this specific association?","options":["Lithium","Lamotrigine","Quetiapine","Valproate / Divalproex"],"answer":"Lithium","explanation":"First-trimester lithium is linked to Ebstein anomaly (tricuspid valve malformation); absolute risk is lower than historically taught, and if continued, levels must be watched closely (clearance rises in pregnancy then falls abruptly at delivery). Valproate's signature is neural-tube defects, not Ebstein; lamotrigine and quetiapine lack this specific cardiac association.","meds":["lithium","lamotrigine","quetiapine","valproate"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["pregnancy"],"source":{"name":"openFDA/DailyMed lithium label — pregnancy (Ebstein anomaly)","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"va_spop_geri_benzo_lorazepam","stem":"An 82-year-old with disabling anxiety has failed non-pharmacologic measures, and a short course of a benzodiazepine is judged unavoidable. To minimize accumulation and fall/delirium risk, which agent is preferred because it is glucuronidated with no active metabolite?","options":["Diazepam","Lorazepam","Flurazepam","Clonazepam"],"answer":"Lorazepam","explanation":"Lorazepam is cleared by glucuronidation (UGT) to an inactive metabolite with no oxidative CYP step, so it does not accumulate the way long-acting/active-metabolite agents do. Diazepam (desmethyldiazepam), flurazepam, and clonazepam are long-acting and accumulate in older adults, worsening falls, sedation, and confusion.","meds":["lorazepam","diazepam","flurazepam","clonazepam"],"disorder":"Generalized anxiety disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["elderly"],"source":{"name":"Beers-type reasoning; deck geriatric/metabolism fields","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"va_spop_geri_amitriptyline_avoid","stem":"A 76-year-old with recurrent depression, a history of falls, constipation, and mild cognitive impairment needs an antidepressant. Which agent is best AVOIDED because it is the most anticholinergic/orthostatic and is on Beers-type lists?","options":["Amitriptyline","Sertraline","Mirtazapine","Bupropion"],"answer":"Amitriptyline","explanation":"Amitriptyline is the most anticholinergic and orthostatic antidepressant (falls, confusion, constipation, urinary retention) and is Beers-listed — avoid in older adults; if a TCA is required, nortriptyline is preferred. Sertraline, mirtazapine, and bupropion are far less anticholinergic and more appropriate here.","meds":["amitriptyline","sertraline","mirtazapine","bupropion"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["elderly","contraindication"],"source":{"name":"Beers-type reasoning; deck amitriptyline geriatric field","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"va_spop_geri_ssri_hyponatremia","stem":"A 79-year-old woman started on an SSRI three weeks ago for depression presents with new confusion, unsteadiness, and headache. Serum sodium is 124 mmol/L; she is euvolemic with concentrated urine. What best explains this picture?","options":["SSRI-induced hyponatremia (SIADH)","Serotonin syndrome","Lithium toxicity","Anticholinergic toxicity"],"answer":"SSRI-induced hyponatremia (SIADH)","explanation":"SSRIs are a common cause of SIADH/hyponatremia, especially in older women within the first weeks of therapy — euvolemic hyponatremia with inappropriately concentrated urine fits. Serotonin syndrome causes clonus/hyperthermia (not isolated low sodium), lithium toxicity gives coarse tremor/ataxia, and anticholinergic toxicity gives dry skin and delirium without hyponatremia.","meds":["sertraline"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["elderly","hyponatremia"],"source":{"name":"FRCPC geriatric psychopharmacology; deck SSRI geriatric fields","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"va_spop_renal_lithium","stem":"A 74-year-old on bipolar maintenance develops chronic kidney disease with a declining eGFR. Which maintenance agent demands the greatest caution and dose reduction here because it is excreted unchanged by the kidney and accumulates as clearance falls?","options":["Lithium","Valproate / Divalproex","Lamotrigine","Quetiapine"],"answer":"Lithium","explanation":"Lithium is not metabolized — it is renally cleared unchanged, so falling GFR (and the elderly's reduced clearance) raises the level toward its narrow toxic threshold (>1.5 mmol/L). Valproate, lamotrigine, and quetiapine are hepatically metabolized and are not primarily renally eliminated.","meds":["lithium","valproate","lamotrigine","quetiapine"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["renal"],"source":{"name":"openFDA/DailyMed lithium label — renal elimination; deck metabolism field","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"va_spop_hepatic_oxazepam","stem":"A 58-year-old with decompensated alcohol-related cirrhosis needs a benzodiazepine to manage alcohol withdrawal. Which agent is preferred because it is cleared by glucuronidation and is spared the impaired oxidative metabolism of liver disease?","options":["Diazepam","Chlordiazepoxide","Oxazepam","Clonazepam"],"answer":"Oxazepam","explanation":"Oxazepam undergoes glucuronidation only (no oxidative CYP step), so its clearance is preserved in hepatic impairment — preferred alongside lorazepam/temazepam (the 'LOT' agents). Diazepam and chlordiazepoxide are long-acting, oxidatively metabolized, and accumulate active metabolites in liver disease.","meds":["oxazepam","diazepam","chlordiazepoxide","clonazepam"],"disorder":"Alcohol use disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["hepatic"],"source":{"name":"Deck renalHepaticAdjustment/metabolism fields (glucuronidated benzodiazepines)","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"va_spop_ddi_fluvoxamine_clozapine","stem":"A patient with schizophrenia stabilized on clozapine develops prominent obsessive-compulsive symptoms, and an SSRI is being considered. Which SSRI is the MOST dangerous choice here because it can raise clozapine levels toward toxicity/seizures?","options":["Fluvoxamine","Sertraline","Escitalopram","Citalopram"],"answer":"Fluvoxamine","explanation":"Fluvoxamine is a potent CYP1A2 inhibitor, and clozapine is a 1A2 substrate — combining them can dramatically raise clozapine levels, precipitating toxicity and seizures. Sertraline, escitalopram, and citalopram have minimal 1A2 inhibition and are safer co-prescriptions.","meds":["fluvoxamine","clozapine","sertraline","escitalopram","citalopram"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":3,"tags":["interaction"],"source":{"name":"Deck fluvoxamine/clozapine majorDDI (CYP1A2 inhibition)","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"va_spop_ddi_carbamazepine_ocp","stem":"A 23-year-old woman with bipolar I who relies on a combined oral contraceptive is starting a mood stabilizer. Which agent most requires counselling about contraceptive FAILURE (advise a non-hormonal method) because it is a potent enzyme inducer?","options":["Carbamazepine","Lamotrigine","Lithium","Valproate / Divalproex"],"answer":"Carbamazepine","explanation":"Carbamazepine is a potent CYP3A4 inducer that accelerates metabolism of estrogen/progestin, lowering contraceptive efficacy — counsel a non-hormonal method. Lithium is renally cleared (no induction), valproate is an inhibitor rather than an inducer, and lamotrigine does not reduce contraceptive levels (the interaction runs the other way — estrogen lowers lamotrigine).","meds":["carbamazepine","lamotrigine","lithium","valproate"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["interaction"],"source":{"name":"Deck carbamazepine majorDDI (3A4 induction → contraceptive failure)","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"va_spop_ddi_valproate_lamotrigine","stem":"A patient stabilized on lamotrigine for bipolar maintenance is about to have a second agent added. Which addition would roughly DOUBLE the lamotrigine level and sharply raise the risk of Stevens-Johnson syndrome, mandating that the lamotrigine dose be halved?","options":["Valproate / Divalproex","Carbamazepine","Lithium","Sertraline"],"answer":"Valproate / Divalproex","explanation":"Valproate inhibits lamotrigine glucuronidation, roughly doubling its level and increasing SJS risk — the lamotrigine dose must be halved when they are combined. Carbamazepine does the opposite (induces glucuronidation, lowering lamotrigine); lithium and sertraline do not meaningfully alter lamotrigine levels.","meds":["valproate","lamotrigine","carbamazepine","lithium","sertraline"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":3,"tags":["interaction"],"source":{"name":"Deck valproate/lamotrigine majorDDI (glucuronidation inhibition; SJS)","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"va_spop_ddi_lithium_nsaid_toxicity","stem":"A 62-year-old stable on lithium starts regular ibuprofen for arthritis. Ten days later she has a coarse tremor, unsteady gait, slurred speech, and confusion. Which is the most likely diagnosis?","options":["Lithium toxicity","Serotonin syndrome","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Anticholinergic toxicity"],"answer":"Lithium toxicity","explanation":"NSAIDs reduce renal lithium clearance and raise the level (as thiazides and ACE inhibitors/ARBs do), producing the classic toxicity picture: coarse tremor, ataxia, dysarthria, and confusion. Serotonin syndrome brings clonus/hyperthermia, NMS brings lead-pipe rigidity over days, and anticholinergic toxicity gives dry flushed skin — none fit an NSAID added to lithium.","meds":["lithium"],"disorder":"Bipolar I disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["interaction","overdose"],"source":{"name":"openFDA/DailyMed lithium label — drug interactions (NSAID)","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"va_spop_ddi_maoi_serotonin","stem":"A patient on phenelzine for refractory depression is inadvertently started on sertraline without a washout. Within hours he develops agitation, diaphoresis, hyperthermia, and inducible lower-limb clonus with hyperreflexia. Which is the most likely syndrome?","options":["Serotonin syndrome","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Hypertensive (tyramine) crisis","Anticholinergic toxicity"],"answer":"Serotonin syndrome","explanation":"An MAOI (phenelzine) combined with an SSRI is a classic, potentially fatal cause of serotonin syndrome — rapid onset with neuromuscular excitability (clonus, hyperreflexia, hyperthermia). A tyramine/hypertensive crisis instead follows sympathomimetics/aged foods and presents with severe hypertension and headache rather than clonus; NMS evolves over days with rigidity and hyporeflexia.","meds":["phenelzine","sertraline"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["serotonin","interaction"],"source":{"name":"Deck phenelzine contraindicatedCombos/maoiWashout (serotonin syndrome)","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"va_spop_switch_fluoxetine_maoi_washout","stem":"A patient who failed an SSRI is being switched to an irreversible MAOI (phenelzine). Discontinuing which of these antidepressants requires an unusually long 5-week washout before the MAOI is started, because of its long-half-life active metabolite?","options":["Fluoxetine","Sertraline","Venlafaxine","Paroxetine"],"answer":"Fluoxetine","explanation":"Fluoxetine (via norfluoxetine) has a very long half-life, so a 5-week washout is required before starting an MAOI to avoid serotonin syndrome — versus roughly 2 weeks for shorter-acting agents like sertraline, venlafaxine, and paroxetine. Starting the MAOI too early risks a fatal serotonergic reaction.","meds":["fluoxetine","sertraline","venlafaxine","paroxetine"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["washout","serotonin","interaction"],"source":{"name":"Deck fluoxetine majorDDI / phenelzine maoiWashout (5-week rule)","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"va_spop_ddi_qt_ziprasidone","stem":"A patient with schizophrenia is also on methadone (a QT-prolonging opioid agonist) for opioid use disorder. Which antipsychotic is the LEAST appropriate choice because it prolongs the QT interval more than the other second-generation agents?","options":["Ziprasidone","Aripiprazole","Olanzapine","Lurasidone"],"answer":"Ziprasidone","explanation":"Ziprasidone causes the greatest QT prolongation of the SGAs and should be avoided alongside another QT-prolonging drug such as methadone (additive torsades risk). Aripiprazole, olanzapine, and lurasidone have minimal QT effect and are safer partners here.","meds":["ziprasidone","aripiprazole","olanzapine","lurasidone","methadone"],"disorder":"Schizophrenia","difficulty":2,"tags":["qt","interaction"],"source":{"name":"Deck ziprasidone cardiac/majorDDI (greatest SGA QT); methadone QT","origin":"openfda"}},{"id":"vs_aud_first_line_naltrexone","stem":"A 44-year-old with alcohol use disorder is still drinking heavily and wants pharmacotherapy to cut down. He takes no opioids, and baseline LFTs and renal function are normal. Which agent is the best first-line choice?","options":["Naltrexone","Disulfiram","Acamprosate","Buprenorphine"],"answer":"Naltrexone","explanation":"Naltrexone is a first-line anti-craving agent that blunts the opioid-mediated reward of drinking and reduces heavy-drinking days; it can be started while the patient is still drinking. Disulfiram is an aversive, later-line option needing a highly motivated abstinent patient; acamprosate maintains abstinence best once already abstinent; buprenorphine treats opioid, not alcohol, use disorder.","meds":["naltrexone","disulfiram","acamprosate","buprenorphine"],"disorder":"Alcohol use disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line","craving"],"source":{"name":"CANMAT/CCSA alcohol use disorder","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vs_aud_hepatic_acamprosate","stem":"A 58-year-old with alcohol use disorder has been abstinent for two weeks and now wants relapse-prevention pharmacotherapy. She has established alcoholic cirrhosis with elevated transaminases; renal function is normal. Which agent is safest and most appropriate?","options":["Acamprosate","Naltrexone","Disulfiram","Methadone"],"answer":"Acamprosate","explanation":"Acamprosate is renally excreted unchanged and is not hepatically metabolized, making it the preferred maintenance agent in significant liver disease. Naltrexone and disulfiram are both hepatotoxic and are cautioned/avoided with transaminitis; methadone is an opioid agonist irrelevant to alcohol use disorder.","meds":["acamprosate","naltrexone","disulfiram","methadone"],"disorder":"Alcohol use disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["hepatic","special-population","maintenance"],"source":{"name":"Acamprosate monograph (renal clearance)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vs_aud_disulfiram_reaction","stem":"A patient on medication for alcohol use disorder rinses with an alcohol-containing mouthwash and within minutes develops intense facial flushing, throbbing headache, nausea and vomiting, tachycardia and hypotension. Which reaction is this?","options":["Disulfiram–alcohol reaction","Serotonin syndrome","Anticholinergic toxicity","Precipitated opioid withdrawal"],"answer":"Disulfiram–alcohol reaction","explanation":"Disulfiram irreversibly inhibits aldehyde dehydrogenase; any alcohol exposure (including mouthwash, cough syrup, sauces) causes acetaldehyde accumulation with flushing, headache, nausea, tachycardia and hypotension. The picture is not serotonergic, anticholinergic, or opioid-withdrawal in nature.","meds":["disulfiram"],"disorder":"Alcohol use disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["recognise-syndrome","interaction"],"source":{"name":"Disulfiram monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vs_oud_first_line_bupnx","stem":"A 29-year-old with opioid use disorder presents to an outpatient clinic to start opioid agonist therapy. He is medically stable and adherence/safety are priorities. Which agent is recommended as first-line?","options":["Buprenorphine / Naloxone","Methadone","Naltrexone","Naloxone"],"answer":"Buprenorphine / Naloxone","explanation":"CRISM guidance favours buprenorphine/naloxone as first-line opioid agonist therapy because the partial agonist has a ceiling on respiratory depression and a far safer overdose profile than methadone. Methadone is a second-line full agonist; naltrexone is an antagonist requiring prior abstinence; naloxone is an acute rescue drug, not maintenance.","meds":["buprenorphine_naloxone","methadone","naltrexone","naloxone"],"disorder":"Opioid use disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line","oat"],"source":{"name":"CRISM national OAT guideline","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vs_oud_precipitated_withdrawal","stem":"A patient who used a full-agonist opioid a few hours earlier is given a first dose of buprenorphine before objective withdrawal has appeared. Within 30 minutes he becomes acutely diaphoretic, nauseated, and markedly worse than before. What has happened?","options":["Precipitated opioid withdrawal","Opioid overdose","Serotonin syndrome","Disulfiram–alcohol reaction"],"answer":"Precipitated opioid withdrawal","explanation":"Buprenorphine's high mu-receptor affinity but low intrinsic activity displaces the full agonist and abruptly drops receptor activation, precipitating withdrawal when started too early. Induction should wait for objective withdrawal (e.g. COWS) or use a micro-dosing protocol; this is the opposite of overdose and is not serotonergic.","meds":["buprenorphine","buprenorphine_naloxone"],"disorder":"Opioid use disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["recognise-syndrome","precipitated-withdrawal","induction"],"source":{"name":"Buprenorphine induction (COWS)","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vs_oud_overdose_rescue","stem":"A man is found unresponsive with a respiratory rate of 6, pinpoint pupils, and drug paraphernalia nearby. Which agent is the immediate pharmacologic rescue?","options":["Naloxone","Naltrexone","Methadone","Buprenorphine"],"answer":"Naloxone","explanation":"Naloxone is a short-acting opioid antagonist that rapidly reverses opioid-induced respiratory depression; watch for re-narcotization as it wears off. Naltrexone is a maintenance antagonist (not for acute rescue), while methadone and buprenorphine are agonists that would worsen the overdose.","meds":["naloxone","naltrexone","methadone","buprenorphine"],"disorder":"Opioid use disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["overdose","rescue"],"source":{"name":"Naloxone monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vs_oud_methadone_qt","stem":"A patient on methadone maintenance has his dose escalated above 100 mg/day and is also started on a QT-prolonging antibiotic. He develops syncope; ECG shows a markedly prolonged QTc. Which methadone-related complication does this represent?","options":["QT prolongation / torsades de pointes","Serotonin syndrome","Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Opioid withdrawal"],"answer":"QT prolongation / torsades de pointes","explanation":"Methadone causes dose-dependent QT prolongation and torsades, so an ECG is obtained at baseline, around 30 days, and periodically, especially above 100 mg/day or with additive QT drugs. This is a cardiac-conduction event, not a serotonergic, dopaminergic (NMS), or withdrawal phenomenon.","meds":["methadone"],"disorder":"Opioid use disorder","difficulty":3,"tags":["qt","monitoring","recognise-syndrome"],"source":{"name":"Methadone monograph (QT/ECG)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vs_oud_naltrexone_washout","stem":"A patient with opioid use disorder has completed a supervised withdrawal and has been opioid-free for 10 days. He prefers a non-agonist agent that will block relapse without any abuse potential. Which is appropriate?","options":["Naltrexone","Methadone","Buprenorphine / Naloxone","Acamprosate"],"answer":"Naltrexone","explanation":"Naltrexone is an opioid antagonist for the detoxified patient; it requires roughly 7–10 opioid-free days first, otherwise it precipitates withdrawal, and the extended-release depot aids adherence. Methadone and buprenorphine/naloxone are agonist therapies; acamprosate is for alcohol, not opioid, use disorder.","meds":["naltrexone","methadone","buprenorphine_naloxone","acamprosate"],"disorder":"Opioid use disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["washout","switching","relapse-prevention"],"source":{"name":"Naltrexone monograph (opioid-free interval)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vs_tobacco_varenicline_first","stem":"A motivated 50-year-old smoker with no psychiatric or seizure history wants the single most effective pharmacotherapy for smoking cessation. Which do you recommend?","options":["Varenicline","Bupropion","Clonidine","Naltrexone"],"answer":"Varenicline","explanation":"Varenicline, an α4β2 nicotinic partial agonist, is the most effective single agent for smoking cessation and is started about a week before the quit date (nausea and vivid dreams are the hallmark effects). Bupropion is effective but less so, clonidine is second-line, and naltrexone is not a cessation aid.","meds":["varenicline","bupropion","clonidine","naltrexone"],"disorder":"Tobacco use disorder","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line"],"source":{"name":"Varenicline monograph / EAGLES","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vs_tobacco_bupropion_dual","stem":"A 40-year-old smoker also has untreated major depression and no seizure or eating disorder history. He would prefer a single medication that helps both his mood and quitting smoking. Which is the best choice?","options":["Bupropion","Varenicline","Escitalopram","Clonidine"],"answer":"Bupropion","explanation":"Bupropion treats major depression and is an established smoking-cessation aid (marketed as Zyban), making it the efficient single agent here — provided there is no seizure disorder or eating disorder, in which it is contraindicated. Varenicline aids cessation but not depression, escitalopram treats depression but not smoking, and clonidine is only a second-line cessation option.","meds":["bupropion","varenicline","escitalopram","clonidine"],"disorder":"Tobacco use disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["dual-purpose","depression"],"source":{"name":"Bupropion monograph (MDD + Zyban)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vs_adhd_stimulant_first_line","stem":"A healthy 24-year-old with newly diagnosed ADHD, no cardiac disease and no substance-use concerns, wants the most effective pharmacotherapy. Which agent class is first-line?","options":["Lisdexamfetamine","Atomoxetine","Guanfacine XR","Clonidine"],"answer":"Lisdexamfetamine","explanation":"Stimulants are the most effective, first-line treatment for ADHD in patients without a contraindication; lisdexamfetamine is a stimulant (a prodrug of dextroamphetamine). Atomoxetine, guanfacine XR, and clonidine are non-stimulants reserved mainly for patients who cannot tolerate, misuse, or fail stimulants.","meds":["lisdexamfetamine","atomoxetine","guanfacine","clonidine"],"disorder":"ADHD","difficulty":1,"tags":["first-line","stimulant"],"source":{"name":"CADDRA ADHD guideline","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vs_adhd_misuse_atomoxetine","stem":"A 30-year-old with ADHD has an active stimulant use disorder and a documented history of diverting medication. He needs effective ADHD treatment with the lowest misuse and diversion risk. Which agent is preferred?","options":["Atomoxetine","Dextroamphetamine","Methylphenidate","Mixed Amphetamine Salts"],"answer":"Atomoxetine","explanation":"Atomoxetine is a non-controlled selective norepinephrine reuptake inhibitor with no abuse or diversion potential, making it preferred when misuse risk is high (it takes several weeks to work). Dextroamphetamine, methylphenidate, and mixed amphetamine salts are all controlled stimulants with abuse liability.","meds":["atomoxetine","dextroamphetamine","methylphenidate","amphetamine_salts"],"disorder":"ADHD","difficulty":2,"tags":["misuse","special-population"],"source":{"name":"Atomoxetine monograph (non-controlled NRI)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vs_adhd_cardiac_avoid_stimulant","stem":"A 15-year-old with ADHD is found to have hypertrophic cardiomyopathy on cardiology work-up. Which ADHD medication is the most clearly contraindicated?","options":["Lisdexamfetamine","Atomoxetine","Guanfacine XR","Clonidine"],"answer":"Lisdexamfetamine","explanation":"Stimulants such as lisdexamfetamine carry a risk of sudden cardiac death in patients with serious structural heart disease and should be avoided in hypertrophic cardiomyopathy. The non-stimulants are comparatively safer here — atomoxetine raises HR/BP modestly, and the α2 agonists tend to lower them — but the stimulant is the one to avoid outright.","meds":["lisdexamfetamine","atomoxetine","guanfacine","clonidine"],"disorder":"ADHD","difficulty":2,"tags":["cardiac","contraindication"],"source":{"name":"Stimulant cardiac warnings","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vs_adhd_maoi_guanfacine","stem":"An adult with treatment-refractory depression is stable on phenelzine and now needs treatment for comorbid ADHD. Which agent can be used without risking a hypertensive crisis?","options":["Guanfacine XR","Methylphenidate","Lisdexamfetamine","Atomoxetine"],"answer":"Guanfacine XR","explanation":"Stimulants and atomoxetine are contraindicated with an MAOI or within 14 days of stopping one because of hypertensive-crisis risk. The α2A agonist guanfacine XR carries no MAOI-washout requirement and can be used, with monitoring for bradycardia and hypotension.","meds":["guanfacine","methylphenidate","lisdexamfetamine","atomoxetine","phenelzine"],"disorder":"ADHD","difficulty":2,"tags":["maoi","interaction"],"source":{"name":"Stimulant/atomoxetine MAOI washout","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vs_adhd_mechanism_amphetamine","stem":"On an oral board, you are asked which ADHD stimulant works primarily by driving presynaptic RELEASE of dopamine and norepinephrine (reversing the transporters), rather than by pure reuptake blockade. Which is it?","options":["Dextroamphetamine","Methylphenidate","Atomoxetine","Guanfacine XR"],"answer":"Dextroamphetamine","explanation":"Amphetamines such as dextroamphetamine enter the neuron and trigger vesicular release of dopamine and norepinephrine (and block reuptake). Methylphenidate is a pure reuptake blocker, atomoxetine is a selective NE reuptake inhibitor, and guanfacine is a postsynaptic α2A agonist — none of which drive presynaptic release.","meds":["dextroamphetamine","methylphenidate","atomoxetine","guanfacine"],"disorder":"ADHD","difficulty":3,"tags":["mechanism"],"source":{"name":"Stimulant pharmacology","origin":"authored"}},{"id":"vs_insomnia_elderly_dora","stem":"A 78-year-old with chronic insomnia and a prior fall wants ongoing pharmacotherapy. You want to minimize fall risk and next-day impairment. Which agent is the most appropriate?","options":["Daridorexant","Zopiclone","Temazepam","Flurazepam"],"answer":"Daridorexant","explanation":"Daridorexant is a dual orexin antagonist with a short half-life and the least next-day impairment, avoiding the GABA-mediated fall/confusion risk of the other options. Benzodiazepine hypnotics (temazepam, flurazepam) and Z-drugs (zopiclone) are Beers-listed to avoid in older adults, and flurazepam's long-lived active metabolite accumulates.","meds":["daridorexant","zopiclone","temazepam","flurazepam"],"disorder":"Insomnia","difficulty":2,"tags":["elderly","beers"],"source":{"name":"Beers criteria / daridorexant monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vs_insomnia_zdrug_complex_behaviour","stem":"Two weeks after starting a hypnotic, a patient's partner reports she has driven the car and prepared food while asleep, with no memory of these events the next morning. Which drug is the classic cause of this?","options":["Zolpidem","Melatonin","Ramelteon","Buspirone"],"answer":"Zolpidem","explanation":"Z-drugs such as zolpidem carry a boxed/serious warning for complex sleep behaviours — sleep-driving, sleep-eating and sleep-walking with anterograde amnesia — and should be discontinued if these occur. Melatonin, the melatonin agonist ramelteon, and the anxiolytic buspirone are not characteristically implicated.","meds":["zolpidem","melatonin","ramelteon","buspirone"],"disorder":"Insomnia","difficulty":2,"tags":["complex-sleep-behaviour","z-drug"],"source":{"name":"Zolpidem monograph (boxed warning)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vs_insomnia_ramelteon_fluvoxamine","stem":"A patient stabilized on fluvoxamine for OCD now needs a hypnotic for sleep-onset insomnia. Which agent is contraindicated because of a major CYP1A2 interaction?","options":["Ramelteon","Zopiclone","Trazodone","Temazepam"],"answer":"Ramelteon","explanation":"Fluvoxamine is a potent CYP1A2 inhibitor that dramatically raises ramelteon (and melatonin) levels, so the combination is contraindicated. Zopiclone, trazodone, and temazepam are not CYP1A2-dependent in the same way and are not contraindicated with fluvoxamine on that basis.","meds":["ramelteon","fluvoxamine","zopiclone","trazodone","temazepam"],"disorder":"Insomnia","difficulty":3,"tags":["interaction","cyp1a2"],"source":{"name":"Ramelteon monograph (fluvoxamine)","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vs_insomnia_maintenance_doxepin","stem":"A 72-year-old has sleep-MAINTENANCE insomnia with frequent early-morning awakenings and wants a non-controlled option with a low fall/amnesia risk. Which is the best choice?","options":["Doxepin","Triazolam","Zolpidem","Flurazepam"],"answer":"Doxepin","explanation":"At low dose (3–6 mg) doxepin acts as a selective H1 antihistamine for sleep maintenance, is non-controlled, and is comparatively better studied in older adults. Triazolam causes marked amnesia and early rebound, and zolpidem and flurazepam are on Beers avoid lists for older adults.","meds":["doxepin","triazolam","zolpidem","flurazepam"],"disorder":"Insomnia","difficulty":3,"tags":["elderly","maintenance"],"source":{"name":"Low-dose doxepin monograph","origin":"monograph"}},{"id":"vs_insomnia_depression_mirtazapine","stem":"A 60-year-old with major depression also has prominent insomnia, poor appetite and weight loss. Which single agent best addresses all of these together?","options":["Mirtazapine","Trazodone","Zopiclone","Bupropion"],"answer":"Mirtazapine","explanation":"Mirtazapine treats depression while its sedating (especially at low dose) and appetite-stimulating properties target insomnia, poor appetite and weight loss in one agent. Trazodone and zopiclone address only sleep, and bupropion is activating and can worsen insomnia.","meds":["mirtazapine","trazodone","zopiclone","bupropion"],"disorder":"Major depressive disorder","difficulty":2,"tags":["insomnia","depression","special-population"],"source":{"name":"Mirtazapine monograph","origin":"monograph"}}];
